1
00:00:14,014 --> 00:00:18,451
We're here with the two cool ladies,
Kim Young-ok and Park Jun-myun.

2
00:00:18,518 --> 00:00:22,055
Jun-myun is known as a great talent
who can act, sing,

3
00:00:22,122 --> 00:00:23,323
and even dance,

4
00:00:23,390 --> 00:00:27,527
recognized in the world of entertainment
as a natural-born entertainer.

5
00:00:27,594 --> 00:00:30,430
You've been busy lately
with both acting and performing, right?

6
00:00:30,497 --> 00:00:32,999
-Yes, I've been a bit busy lately.
-I see.

7
00:00:33,066 --> 00:00:36,870
<i>I've been doing a nationwide tour</i>
<i>of </i>Mamma Mia! <i>the musical.</i>

8
00:00:36,936 --> 00:00:38,171
-Legendary.
-And I've been filming

9
00:00:38,238 --> 00:00:42,242
a series called <i>Perfect Crown,</i>
which will go on air in spring,

10
00:00:42,308 --> 00:00:45,412
-starring IU and… Yes.
-IU and Byeon Woo-seok.

11
00:00:45,478 --> 00:00:48,581
So I've been working hard
toward the end of the production.

12
00:00:48,648 --> 00:00:49,949
Of course, she's in dramas,

13
00:00:50,016 --> 00:00:52,252
but she debuted
as a musical performer at age 19.

14
00:00:52,318 --> 00:00:53,620
-Really?
-Yes.

15
00:00:53,686 --> 00:00:54,888
-So you know,
-19 years old?

16
00:00:54,954 --> 00:00:58,158
she has starred in many musicals
you would instantly recognize.

17
00:00:58,224 --> 00:00:59,325
<i>The Last Empress,</i>

18
00:00:59,392 --> 00:01:01,428
-By ACOM.
-<i>Grease, Chicago,</i>

19
00:01:01,494 --> 00:01:04,431
<i>-Les Misérables, </i>and currently,<i> Mamma Mia!</i>
-That's amazing.

20
00:01:04,497 --> 00:01:07,033
-She's been in every production.
-It's quite a career.

21
00:01:07,100 --> 00:01:10,003
One of your biggest fans
is among our chefs.

22
00:01:10,070 --> 00:01:11,271
What? Who is it?

23
00:01:11,337 --> 00:01:14,808
I've watched <i>Mamma Mia! </i>at least 20 times,

24
00:01:14,874 --> 00:01:16,276
starting with the premiere.

25
00:01:16,342 --> 00:01:18,812
I was amazed to see her
in the most recent production.

26
00:01:18,878 --> 00:01:21,581
I also admired your work in <i>Mamma Mia!</i>

27
00:01:21,648 --> 00:01:22,949
She's irreplaceable, isn't she?

28
00:01:23,016 --> 00:01:24,050
I completely agree.

29
00:01:24,117 --> 00:01:27,720
Your performance was flawless.
I never got a chance to tell you that.

30
00:01:27,787 --> 00:01:28,621
Thank you.

31
00:01:28,688 --> 00:01:30,757
-You were really great.
-She was.

32
00:01:30,824 --> 00:01:34,461
It's such an honor for me
that he would sing the number

33
00:01:34,527 --> 00:01:36,696
-"Chiquitita" right here.
-It's great.

34
00:01:36,763 --> 00:01:39,065
-That's her number.
-I'll grant you extra points today.

35
00:01:39,399 --> 00:01:40,934
LET ME BOW AND SHARE MY GRATITUDE

36
00:01:42,268 --> 00:01:43,670
I'm so jealous.

37
00:01:43,736 --> 00:01:46,139
I hear Chef Jong-won has a favor
to ask of Jun-myun

38
00:01:46,206 --> 00:01:47,707
now that he's here with her.

39
00:01:47,774 --> 00:01:48,708
-Is that right?
-Yes.

40
00:01:48,775 --> 00:01:50,076
Whoa. Are you serious?

41
00:01:50,143 --> 00:01:52,178
I'm a huge musical fan,
and I love Broadway.

42
00:01:52,245 --> 00:01:53,847
-He loves live performances.
-I look it up often.

43
00:01:53,913 --> 00:01:54,981
HEHEHE

44
00:01:55,048 --> 00:01:57,383
I'm sorry. My nose suddenly got runny.
One second, please.

45
00:01:57,450 --> 00:01:58,918
REACHING DOWN

46
00:01:58,985 --> 00:02:00,753
I have some tissues.

47
00:02:00,820 --> 00:02:01,788
How sweet.

48
00:02:03,022 --> 00:02:04,190
How sweet of him.

49
00:02:04,524 --> 00:02:06,159
HEART SKIPS A BEAT

50
00:02:06,226 --> 00:02:08,194
I realized while sitting next to you

51
00:02:08,261 --> 00:02:10,396
that the color of your eyes is unusual.

52
00:02:10,463 --> 00:02:12,132
-The color of his eyes?
-Yes.

53
00:02:12,198 --> 00:02:14,667
It's the type of color
that bewitches people.

54
00:02:14,734 --> 00:02:16,269
-Hey, stop.
-What are they like?

55
00:02:16,336 --> 00:02:18,404
She's so into him.

56
00:02:18,471 --> 00:02:20,273
-Do not fight him today.
-Are they special?

57
00:02:20,340 --> 00:02:21,174
Not today.

58
00:02:21,241 --> 00:02:24,677
His eyes remind me of a vast lake.

59
00:02:24,744 --> 00:02:28,148
-His eyes are deep, like a lake.
-They're deep?

60
00:02:28,214 --> 00:02:29,716
You should be careful.

61
00:02:29,782 --> 00:02:31,584
They're so deep, you might drown in them.

62
00:02:31,951 --> 00:02:34,387
NO DIVING ALLOWED INTO HIS EYES

63
00:02:34,454 --> 00:02:38,992
There's another reason why
there isn't enough of her to go around.

64
00:02:39,058 --> 00:02:42,862
She recently began a kimchi business.

65
00:02:42,929 --> 00:02:45,865
I always made my own kimchi

66
00:02:45,932 --> 00:02:48,201
and even gave it out to my friends.

67
00:02:48,268 --> 00:02:51,437
Then one day, Kim Hye-soo suggested
that I should turn it into a business.

68
00:02:51,504 --> 00:02:53,206
-Because it was so good?
-Yes, that's why,

69
00:02:53,273 --> 00:02:55,208
-and it turned out quite nicely.
-Really?

70
00:02:55,275 --> 00:02:56,910
-That's not so easy.
-So today,

71
00:02:56,976 --> 00:02:59,512
I brought one box each
to give out to everyone.

72
00:02:59,579 --> 00:03:01,581
-You did.
-I love people who give me kimchi.

73
00:03:01,648 --> 00:03:04,951
I have to bring this up
because I always get it from her.

74
00:03:05,018 --> 00:03:07,954
Imagine how much kimchi
I must've had in all of my life.

75
00:03:08,021 --> 00:03:10,390
-I usually make some myself.
-Yes, of course.

76
00:03:10,456 --> 00:03:13,626
-But her kimchi is unbelievable.
-Is that so?

77
00:03:13,693 --> 00:03:15,695
It really hits the spot.

78
00:03:15,762 --> 00:03:17,497
I couldn't believe how good it was.

79
00:03:17,564 --> 00:03:21,868
For your kimchi to be good,
you first need a sensitive palate.

80
00:03:21,935 --> 00:03:23,736
Since I was young,

81
00:03:23,803 --> 00:03:27,507
we were the kind of family
that made 200 to 300 heads of kimchi.

82
00:03:27,574 --> 00:03:29,275
-Gosh, 200 to 300 heads?
-We even made

83
00:03:29,342 --> 00:03:32,478
different kinds of <i>jang,</i>
traditional Korean condiments.

84
00:03:32,545 --> 00:03:33,913
I guess my palate was trained early.

85
00:03:33,980 --> 00:03:36,783
-That's important.
-It could've had an impact on me.

86
00:03:36,849 --> 00:03:39,319
Also, I often travel
all around the country to perform, so…

87
00:03:39,385 --> 00:03:41,988
You must know lots of delicious joints.

88
00:03:42,055 --> 00:03:43,289
Just tell me the region.

89
00:03:43,356 --> 00:03:44,657
THEN I'LL GIVE YOU A RESTAURANT

90
00:03:44,724 --> 00:03:46,459
-May I really? Gangwon-do.
-Sure.

91
00:03:46,526 --> 00:03:49,429
-A great place in Gangwon-do.
-You should go to Jungang Market.

92
00:03:49,495 --> 00:03:51,297
There's a place that makes a mean <i>ongsimi.</i>

93
00:03:51,364 --> 00:03:53,132
-Potato dumpling soup.
-It's famous there.

94
00:03:53,199 --> 00:03:54,267
Let's say you're in Daegu.

95
00:03:54,334 --> 00:03:57,437
-Charcoal-grilled bulgogi is famous there.
-That's a good one.

96
00:03:57,503 --> 00:04:00,173
-Go to T restaurant for that and udon.
-T restaurant.

97
00:04:00,607 --> 00:04:02,108
CURIOUS

98
00:04:02,175 --> 00:04:03,977
We're now in Busan.

99
00:04:04,043 --> 00:04:07,080
I somehow end up eating <i>tteokbokki</i>
whenever I'm in Busan.

100
00:04:07,347 --> 00:04:08,348
TTEOKBOKKI IN BUSAN?

101
00:04:08,414 --> 00:04:10,850
-It's B place near Haeundae.
-Yes, that place is famous.

102
00:04:10,917 --> 00:04:15,054
They had a business there for a long time
and recently moved.

103
00:04:15,121 --> 00:04:17,156
I was there not too long ago.

104
00:04:17,223 --> 00:04:18,691
She can answer back immediately.

105
00:04:18,758 --> 00:04:19,959
Furthermore,

106
00:04:20,026 --> 00:04:23,997
she has specific restaurants she visits
depending on her physical condition.

107
00:04:24,063 --> 00:04:26,899
Yes, when I feel under the weather,

108
00:04:26,966 --> 00:04:28,835
there's this <i>seolleongtang,</i>
ox bone soup place I go to.

109
00:04:29,335 --> 00:04:30,370
INTERESTED

110
00:04:31,004 --> 00:04:31,971
What is it?

111
00:04:32,038 --> 00:04:34,574
-It's M restaurant in Mapo-gu.
-M restaurant.

112
00:04:34,641 --> 00:04:37,176
-That place is so good.
-Me too. I always go there.

113
00:04:37,243 --> 00:04:39,045
-I go there often too.
-In Mapo-gu.

114
00:04:39,112 --> 00:04:41,147
The soup is fantastic.

115
00:04:41,214 --> 00:04:44,050
-I always get the bigger size.
-You have to.

116
00:04:44,117 --> 00:04:45,151
It warms you up right away.

117
00:04:45,218 --> 00:04:46,719
<i>Seolleongtang</i> is all the same, though.

118
00:04:46,786 --> 00:04:48,354
-It's not.
-No, it's not.

119
00:04:48,421 --> 00:04:49,322
-No?
-That place is real.

120
00:04:49,389 --> 00:04:50,990
The brisket there is amazing too.

121
00:04:51,057 --> 00:04:52,225
Is it different?

122
00:04:52,292 --> 00:04:54,327
-They can be curt, though.
-You should try it.

123
00:04:54,394 --> 00:04:55,928
When you feel under the weather,

124
00:04:55,995 --> 00:04:57,664
don't you usually lose your appetite?

125
00:04:58,364 --> 00:05:00,933
-Well, my appetite's fine.
-Is it?

126
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:02,635
-You need to eat well.
-Do you eat it all?

127
00:05:02,702 --> 00:05:04,237
-Of course.
-Finish the whole bowl?

128
00:05:04,304 --> 00:05:05,672
-Yes, the entire bowl.
-I see.

129
00:05:05,738 --> 00:05:09,175
-I'm sure some foods are seasonal.
-You're right.

130
00:05:09,242 --> 00:05:11,644
<i>Gwamegi,</i> half-dried Pacific saury,
is in season right now.

131
00:05:11,711 --> 00:05:13,780
<i>-Gwamegi.</i>
-And oysters are great these days.

132
00:05:13,846 --> 00:05:15,081
-They're in season.
-Oysters sound good.

133
00:05:15,148 --> 00:05:16,449
-Between summer and winter?
-I'll eat those.

134
00:05:16,516 --> 00:05:19,519
Grapes are best in that period.

135
00:05:19,585 --> 00:05:21,087
-Grapes.
-Grapes are good.

136
00:05:21,154 --> 00:05:22,922
There's a place I always order from,

137
00:05:22,989 --> 00:05:25,358
-a place in Pocheon.
-Pocheon grapes.

138
00:05:25,425 --> 00:05:27,994
They call me at the beginning of September

139
00:05:28,061 --> 00:05:29,762
to tell me that the grapes are ready,

140
00:05:29,829 --> 00:05:32,665
and I send those to my acquaintances.
For the year…

141
00:05:32,732 --> 00:05:33,766
I've never had those.

142
00:05:33,833 --> 00:05:35,535
I'll send some next year.

143
00:05:35,601 --> 00:05:37,570
A BIG SMILE

144
00:05:37,637 --> 00:05:39,105
-How about apples?
-Apples?

145
00:05:39,172 --> 00:05:41,107
-I got a place in Mungyeong.
-Mungyeong.

146
00:05:41,341 --> 00:05:42,608
INPUTTING: MUNGYEONG APPLES

147
00:05:42,675 --> 00:05:44,277
Instead of just ordering those,

148
00:05:44,344 --> 00:05:46,145
why don't you work in tandem with chefs

149
00:05:46,212 --> 00:05:47,580
and start a business as a supplier?

150
00:05:47,647 --> 00:05:49,649
-Hey, that's not a bad idea.
-That's not a bad idea.

151
00:05:49,716 --> 00:05:52,485
Those of you who'll cook
with ingredients from her fridge

152
00:05:53,052 --> 00:05:54,587
-will have to brace yourselves.
-Yes.

153
00:05:54,654 --> 00:05:58,057
-She has her own standard in food.
-Yes, she has a standard.

154
00:05:58,124 --> 00:06:00,860
Let's find out what kind of philosophy
she holds inside her fridge.

155
00:06:00,927 --> 00:06:03,496
We're about to open up Jun-myun's fridge.

156
00:06:03,563 --> 00:06:05,064
Is this for you and your husband?

157
00:06:05,131 --> 00:06:07,233
-Yes, the two of us.
-The two of you.

158
00:06:07,300 --> 00:06:08,701
Will we see traces of your husband?

159
00:06:08,768 --> 00:06:10,103
-You will.
-Is that so?

160
00:06:10,169 --> 00:06:11,404
When he gets drunk,

161
00:06:11,471 --> 00:06:13,873
he has a habit of buying odd things
at a convenience store.

162
00:06:14,240 --> 00:06:16,743
DRUNK SHOPPING
AT A CONVENIENCE STORE

163
00:06:16,809 --> 00:06:20,279
What kind of ingredients does she have
as someone who has a philosophy on food

164
00:06:20,346 --> 00:06:21,881
and a kimchi business?

165
00:06:21,948 --> 00:06:24,784
-We present Jun-myun's fridge!
-Fridge!

166
00:06:25,918 --> 00:06:27,987
MURMURS OF SATISFACTION

167
00:06:28,054 --> 00:06:29,655
It's fully stocked!

168
00:06:30,223 --> 00:06:32,225
PRESENTING JUN-MYUN'S FRIDGE

169
00:06:32,291 --> 00:06:33,826
It's fully stocked!

170
00:06:34,527 --> 00:06:35,928
FILLED TO THE BRIM

171
00:06:35,995 --> 00:06:38,097
-You can see it.
-She has lots of <i>jang</i> and stuff.

172
00:06:38,164 --> 00:06:40,733
It feels like
it's from a restaurant business.

173
00:06:40,800 --> 00:06:42,135
It looks like it's for a restaurant.

174
00:06:42,201 --> 00:06:43,503
-A Korean restaurant.
-Right?

175
00:06:43,569 --> 00:06:46,005
Like the CEO of a kimchi business she is,

176
00:06:46,072 --> 00:06:47,573
-these are all <i>jeotgal.</i>
-All of them.

177
00:06:47,640 --> 00:06:50,543
Many of them seem to be
something that I do not know very well.

178
00:06:50,610 --> 00:06:52,512
I need those <i>jeotgal</i>, salted seafood,

179
00:06:52,578 --> 00:06:56,015
to make kimchi, such as yellow croaker,
Japanese scaled sardine, and anchovy.

180
00:06:56,282 --> 00:06:57,116
SUCH A VARIETY

181
00:06:57,183 --> 00:06:59,318
What's the most important <i>jeotgal?</i>

182
00:06:59,385 --> 00:07:01,421
-Salted yellow croaker.
-Salted yellow croaker.

183
00:07:01,487 --> 00:07:02,922
-This is it.
-That's important.

184
00:07:02,989 --> 00:07:05,291
It adds depth to the taste.

185
00:07:05,558 --> 00:07:06,826
SUNG-JUN IS SO CURIOUS

186
00:07:06,893 --> 00:07:08,194
-I'm curious.
-Yellow croaker?

187
00:07:08,261 --> 00:07:11,431
I made that with yellow croaker.

188
00:07:11,497 --> 00:07:13,065
-You have to use that juice.
-Yellow croaker.

189
00:07:13,132 --> 00:07:17,103
<i>My family always made the </i>jeotgal <i>at home</i>
<i>before we made kimchi.</i>

190
00:07:17,170 --> 00:07:18,471
Just like my mom.

191
00:07:18,538 --> 00:07:20,706
-It smells awful when you boil it.
-It does.

192
00:07:20,773 --> 00:07:23,042
But I need that flavor,
so I always end up doing it.

193
00:07:23,109 --> 00:07:24,010
It smells pretty bad.

194
00:07:24,076 --> 00:07:26,245
-A family recipe you learned growing up.
-Yes.

195
00:07:26,312 --> 00:07:28,347
I see some side dishes
on the second shelf.

196
00:07:28,414 --> 00:07:30,349
-Are these the usual side dishes?
-Yes.

197
00:07:30,416 --> 00:07:32,718
I take time to make those for my husband.

198
00:07:32,785 --> 00:07:34,987
-That's pickling melon.
-Pickling melon?

199
00:07:35,054 --> 00:07:37,390
-Pickling melon?
-It's called pickling melon,

200
00:07:37,457 --> 00:07:39,959
and it's grown only in Gunsan.

201
00:07:40,026 --> 00:07:41,994
-It's like Korean melon.
-It's similar to Korean melon,

202
00:07:42,061 --> 00:07:43,329
but it's longer

203
00:07:43,396 --> 00:07:45,698
and much less sweet.

204
00:07:45,765 --> 00:07:48,167
-The ones that look like yellow squash?
-Yes.

205
00:07:48,234 --> 00:07:50,336
-This is another delicious side dish.
-That one?

206
00:07:50,403 --> 00:07:52,572
-That's tuna <i>ssamjang.</i>
-What?

207
00:07:52,638 --> 00:07:54,307
-I made it.
-Tuna <i>ssamjang?</i>

208
00:07:54,373 --> 00:07:56,142
IT'S HER PERSONAL CREATION

209
00:07:56,209 --> 00:07:58,778
-Mix <i>ssamjang</i> with peanut butter…
-What?

210
00:07:58,845 --> 00:08:01,647
…tuna, and some sesame oil.

211
00:08:01,714 --> 00:08:04,517
-You can finish a bowl of rice with that.
-<i>Ssamjang</i> and peanut butter?

212
00:08:04,584 --> 00:08:06,819
-Yes, I eat it with veggie wraps.
-Her recipes are unique.

213
00:08:06,886 --> 00:08:10,289
-Yes.
-I found some stir-fried anchovies.

214
00:08:10,356 --> 00:08:12,191
Yes, when I make that,

215
00:08:12,258 --> 00:08:13,626
I don't use any soy sauce.

216
00:08:13,693 --> 00:08:15,061
-What?
-How do you season it?

217
00:08:15,127 --> 00:08:16,529
With mayonnaise.

218
00:08:16,596 --> 00:08:19,198
-Mayonnaise?
-Is that enough to season everything?

219
00:08:19,265 --> 00:08:20,566
It's more than enough.

220
00:08:20,633 --> 00:08:21,901
-Anchovies are already salty.
-They are.

221
00:08:22,101 --> 00:08:24,070
IT'S HARD TO IMAGINE…

222
00:08:24,136 --> 00:08:26,239
-You seasoned this with mayo?
-Yes.

223
00:08:26,305 --> 00:08:29,342
You should try it.
It's not salty at all, and it's very good.

224
00:08:29,408 --> 00:08:31,310
-Let's warm up some rice.
-Should we try some?

225
00:08:31,377 --> 00:08:33,246
-Yes, sure.
-Stir-fried anchovies.

226
00:08:33,312 --> 00:08:36,015
We're trying
Jun-myun's stir-fried anchovies.

227
00:08:36,082 --> 00:08:37,250
-Should we microwave it?
-It's hardened.

228
00:08:37,316 --> 00:08:39,118
STRUGGLE

229
00:08:39,185 --> 00:08:40,987
-He's taking so much.
-Mayonnaise and sugar?

230
00:08:41,053 --> 00:08:42,321
No, I'm going to share.

231
00:08:44,023 --> 00:08:45,525
She added sugar and grain syrup.

232
00:08:45,591 --> 00:08:46,692
Just have a taste.

233
00:08:46,759 --> 00:08:48,294
You wanted a lot, didn't you?

234
00:08:48,361 --> 00:08:51,197
-That's way too little.
-I'm telling you. Just have a taste.

235
00:08:51,264 --> 00:08:52,899
-That's the guest's fridge.
-It's fine.

236
00:08:52,965 --> 00:08:54,400
-Don't eat too much.
-She'll understand.

237
00:08:54,467 --> 00:08:56,202
How much do you want anyway?
It's for a taste.

238
00:08:57,103 --> 00:08:57,970
THEY END UP GETTING MORE

239
00:08:58,037 --> 00:08:59,305
Young-ok, please try some.

240
00:08:59,372 --> 00:09:01,607
It's hard to tell
that this was made with mayonnaise.

241
00:09:01,674 --> 00:09:03,509
-I've never heard of it before.
-Can I eat it now?

242
00:09:03,843 --> 00:09:05,578
YUM

243
00:09:07,513 --> 00:09:09,115
SLURP

244
00:09:09,181 --> 00:09:12,685
-They can tell how good a cook you are.
-I can taste the mayo.

245
00:09:12,752 --> 00:09:14,287
I can taste it. It's so good.

246
00:09:14,353 --> 00:09:15,755
-It hits you later.
-Is it good?

247
00:09:15,821 --> 00:09:18,424
It looks good. No, wait. It is good.

248
00:09:18,491 --> 00:09:19,792
AWKWARD

249
00:09:20,526 --> 00:09:21,360
It's good.

250
00:09:21,427 --> 00:09:22,929
-Is it okay?
-It's seasoned perfectly.

251
00:09:22,995 --> 00:09:24,931
I made it with some garlic oil,

252
00:09:24,997 --> 00:09:26,666
so the flavor isn't bad, right?

253
00:09:26,732 --> 00:09:27,800
It's so good.

254
00:09:27,867 --> 00:09:29,135
-It's good.
-It's nice.

255
00:09:29,201 --> 00:09:32,738
I like how it's not overly sweet
like this dish usually is.

256
00:09:32,805 --> 00:09:36,175
-So my secret is not using soy sauce.
-That was it.

257
00:09:36,242 --> 00:09:38,644
-It's really good. I mean it.
-Was it okay?

258
00:09:38,711 --> 00:09:41,747
Stir-frying garlic in oil
must be the kick.

259
00:09:41,814 --> 00:09:44,150
-Don't you love the smell?
-It makes it less fishy too.

260
00:09:44,216 --> 00:09:48,087
Do you have a different recipe
for dishes such as <i>jeyuk-bokkeum?</i>

261
00:09:48,154 --> 00:09:50,856
When I make <i>jeyuk-bokkeum,</i>
stir-fried pork…

262
00:09:50,923 --> 00:09:51,757
CHUCKLE

263
00:09:51,824 --> 00:09:52,658
…I add peach jam.

264
00:09:52,725 --> 00:09:53,559
-What?
-What?

265
00:09:53,626 --> 00:09:55,328
-You use peach jam?
-To add sweetness?

266
00:09:55,394 --> 00:09:58,931
I liked the overall flavor
when I tried making it with that.

267
00:09:58,998 --> 00:10:00,633
I guess pork and peaches go well together.

268
00:10:00,700 --> 00:10:02,268
-They do.
-Is this it?

269
00:10:02,335 --> 00:10:04,937
-But I don't use sugar.
-She uses peach jam to make <i>jeyuk-bokkeum.</i>

270
00:10:05,004 --> 00:10:06,772
-That's a great idea.
-How is it different?

271
00:10:06,839 --> 00:10:11,344
You'll smell a nice whiff of peach
as you eat the stir-fried pork.

272
00:10:11,410 --> 00:10:13,212
-Do you like to experiment?
-Yes, I do.

273
00:10:13,279 --> 00:10:15,014
You seem to like trying different things.

274
00:10:15,081 --> 00:10:17,717
Yes, I like to try adding this and that.

275
00:10:17,783 --> 00:10:21,153
-I'm so glad you're on the show today.
-Me too.

276
00:10:21,220 --> 00:10:24,023
This is the perfect show for her.

277
00:10:24,090 --> 00:10:27,126
And I'm sure you make your own kimchi.

278
00:10:27,193 --> 00:10:28,861
I have kimchi from my business,

279
00:10:28,928 --> 00:10:31,831
but there's young radish kimchi
I made at the end of November.

280
00:10:31,897 --> 00:10:35,468
It should be perfectly ripened by now,
so it would be nice if you all tried it.

281
00:10:35,534 --> 00:10:36,869
We have to try it.

282
00:10:36,936 --> 00:10:38,838
It looks so good.
I haven't had it for a while.

283
00:10:38,904 --> 00:10:41,841
-There's another kick to this kimchi.
-My goodness.

284
00:10:42,041 --> 00:10:43,643
SHE CAN'T HIDE HER KICKS

285
00:10:43,709 --> 00:10:46,779
The young radish kimchi.
Perfectly ripened, she says.

286
00:10:46,846 --> 00:10:48,347
-Time to go.
-Yes.

287
00:10:48,414 --> 00:10:51,684
-My gosh. These already look so good.
-I can't hold myself back.

288
00:10:51,751 --> 00:10:53,319
It already looks so good.

289
00:10:53,386 --> 00:10:55,287
The kick for this kimchi was that

290
00:10:55,354 --> 00:10:56,922
I used Pacific saury <i>jeotgal.</i>

291
00:10:56,989 --> 00:10:58,391
-Pacific saury <i>jeotgal?</i>
-Yes.

292
00:10:58,457 --> 00:11:00,459
You don't even need meat.
Just rice in some water.

293
00:11:00,526 --> 00:11:03,295
You're right! White rice and plain water.

294
00:11:03,362 --> 00:11:05,731
-Please cut it.
-Those are huge. Can I get some greens?

295
00:11:05,798 --> 00:11:06,732
-Whoa.
-Wait a second.

296
00:11:06,799 --> 00:11:08,901
HEY YOUNGEST, CUT IT NICELY

297
00:11:08,968 --> 00:11:12,204
It's about to go a bit sour,
so it's the most delicious right now.

298
00:11:12,271 --> 00:11:14,407
-It should be. My gosh.
-Yes.

299
00:11:14,473 --> 00:11:15,574
This is huge.

300
00:11:15,641 --> 00:11:16,909
It smells so good.

301
00:11:16,976 --> 00:11:19,378
You can figure out someone's family
when you try their kimchi.

302
00:11:19,445 --> 00:11:20,946
-Let's try a piece each.
-All right.

303
00:11:22,081 --> 00:11:23,883
ONE BITE AND HE'S DONE

304
00:11:24,617 --> 00:11:25,718
It's good.

305
00:11:25,785 --> 00:11:26,952
EVERYONE IS AMAZED

306
00:11:27,019 --> 00:11:29,021
I feel like making <i>ramyeon</i> now.

307
00:11:29,088 --> 00:11:31,490
-It's good. It's so good.
-Wouldn't it be nice with <i>ramyeon?</i>

308
00:11:32,625 --> 00:11:33,459
Jun-myun.

309
00:11:33,526 --> 00:11:34,694
Is that all you have?

310
00:11:34,760 --> 00:11:36,328
TRANSLATED: DO YOU HAVE MORE?

311
00:11:36,395 --> 00:11:37,229
This is it.

312
00:11:37,296 --> 00:11:39,098
I have more at home.

313
00:11:39,165 --> 00:11:40,599
-I'll take that tub, then.
-Sure.

314
00:11:40,666 --> 00:11:42,234
Did you hear what Young-ok said?

315
00:11:42,301 --> 00:11:43,469
"I'll take that tub."

316
00:11:43,803 --> 00:11:46,706
IT'S DEADASS GOOD, THOUGH.

317
00:11:46,772 --> 00:11:48,174
We call good dishes rice thieves,

318
00:11:48,240 --> 00:11:49,809
but that's more like a rice robber.

319
00:11:50,042 --> 00:11:51,410
APPROVED AS A GREAT COOK

320
00:11:51,477 --> 00:11:53,245
It looks like you mostly love Korean food.

321
00:11:53,312 --> 00:11:55,014
-I really do.
-I can tell by the ingredients.

322
00:11:55,081 --> 00:11:57,049
I really am mostly into Korean cuisine.

323
00:11:57,116 --> 00:12:00,453
What's your favorite dish
in Korean cuisine?

324
00:12:00,519 --> 00:12:02,788
I'll have to pick <i>japchae.</i>

325
00:12:02,855 --> 00:12:04,824
<i>-Japchae?</i>
-When I go to a restaurant

326
00:12:04,890 --> 00:12:08,094
<i>-and see warm </i>japchae <i>and barley tea,</i>
<i>-That's so delicious.</i>

327
00:12:08,160 --> 00:12:10,663
I know I can trust that place.

328
00:12:10,730 --> 00:12:13,032
-That's why…
-That's why you have these glass noodles.

329
00:12:13,099 --> 00:12:14,967
She has lots of glass noodles stored.

330
00:12:15,034 --> 00:12:17,303
-That explains the glass noodles.
-So no Western cuisine?

331
00:12:17,369 --> 00:12:22,041
I have to make reservations to go there,
so it feels rather distant.

332
00:12:22,108 --> 00:12:23,809
I want to try fine dining restaurants,

333
00:12:24,376 --> 00:12:25,778
but I haven't had it much.

334
00:12:25,845 --> 00:12:29,348
-I see some fruit in the fridge.
-No one's fridge would be this full.

335
00:12:29,915 --> 00:12:32,151
I also found smoked chicken
in the crisper.

336
00:12:32,218 --> 00:12:36,122
That's the thing my husband got
at the convenience store while drunk.

337
00:12:36,555 --> 00:12:38,224
IT'S A MUST VISIT
WHEN YOU'RE TIPSY

338
00:12:38,290 --> 00:12:39,592
That's delicious.

339
00:12:40,626 --> 00:12:42,128
So he hid it in here.

340
00:12:42,194 --> 00:12:43,162
He hid it.

341
00:12:43,229 --> 00:12:45,131
If he left it here, she could go, "Again?"

342
00:12:45,197 --> 00:12:48,734
-Do you enjoy fruit?
-I love it. As I mentioned before,

343
00:12:48,801 --> 00:12:51,470
I really love fruits that are in season.

344
00:12:51,537 --> 00:12:53,539
Let's move on to the freezer.

345
00:12:53,606 --> 00:12:56,142
There are meats on top.

346
00:12:56,208 --> 00:12:57,777
Meats. Do you like meat?

347
00:12:57,843 --> 00:12:58,711
I do.

348
00:12:58,778 --> 00:13:00,913
And let's see. What's this?

349
00:13:00,980 --> 00:13:03,382
That's boiled and prepped tripe.

350
00:13:03,449 --> 00:13:04,617
-Prepped tripe?
-Do you know it?

351
00:13:04,683 --> 00:13:05,885
-It's good.
-All you need

352
00:13:05,951 --> 00:13:08,454
is some hot pot sauce
to stir-fry with that.

353
00:13:08,521 --> 00:13:09,989
It's a wonderful bar snack.

354
00:13:10,055 --> 00:13:11,457
-That has to be good.
-It sounds good.

355
00:13:11,524 --> 00:13:13,058
-I've never seen it before.
-Beef tripe.

356
00:13:13,125 --> 00:13:16,028
I found some seafood too.
Do you also enjoy these?

357
00:13:16,095 --> 00:13:17,396
Yes, I like seafood too.

358
00:13:17,463 --> 00:13:19,198
Meat versus seafood. One, two, three.

359
00:13:19,265 --> 00:13:20,766
-Meat.
-Meat. Okay.

360
00:13:21,267 --> 00:13:23,402
-Immediately.
-That was immediate.

361
00:13:23,469 --> 00:13:27,473
-Do these read "seasoning"?
-I froze leftover kimchi seasoning.

362
00:13:27,540 --> 00:13:31,377
It's easy to pull out and use
when I make fresh kimchi.

363
00:13:31,443 --> 00:13:33,312
It ferments at room temperature,

364
00:13:33,379 --> 00:13:36,282
-so it's in the freezer.
-You can use it later that way.

365
00:13:36,348 --> 00:13:39,151
-I'll grab that too.
-She wants to grab this too.

366
00:13:39,218 --> 00:13:41,353
Are those chili seeds?

367
00:13:41,420 --> 00:13:43,088
-How do you use those?
-Why do you keep these?

368
00:13:43,155 --> 00:13:45,825
I always use it to make kimchi.

369
00:13:45,891 --> 00:13:47,993
-It adds umami.
-It adds

370
00:13:48,060 --> 00:13:51,363
-spicy and refreshing flavor.
-Spicy and refreshing.

371
00:13:51,430 --> 00:13:53,999
-We saw glass noodles out here before.
-There were glass noodles.

372
00:13:54,066 --> 00:13:55,401
-She's just like me.
-And noodles.

373
00:13:55,467 --> 00:13:57,303
-Some pasta.
-I have noodles and pasta.

374
00:13:57,369 --> 00:13:59,238
You must like noodles.

375
00:13:59,305 --> 00:14:01,040
-I love them.
-I see.

376
00:14:01,106 --> 00:14:02,408
<i>Myeon</i> means noodles, and I'm Jun-myun.

377
00:14:02,474 --> 00:14:04,810
-Jun-myun.
-Any noodles you do not enjoy?

378
00:14:04,877 --> 00:14:07,279
Not at all. I love all noodle dishes.

379
00:14:07,346 --> 00:14:08,781
Do you also like bread?

380
00:14:08,848 --> 00:14:11,217
-I love it.
-I see some plain bread.

381
00:14:11,283 --> 00:14:13,118
I can see why she owns a kimchi business.

382
00:14:13,185 --> 00:14:15,487
That was all for Jun-myun's fridge!

383
00:14:15,554 --> 00:14:17,556
DONE CHECKING OUT
JUN-MYUN'S FRIDGE

384
00:14:17,623 --> 00:14:21,293
Now, what are the orders
she's asking of the chefs today?

385
00:14:21,360 --> 00:14:23,729
Let's find out the orders.

386
00:14:23,796 --> 00:14:24,763
The first one.

387
00:14:25,297 --> 00:14:28,033
-Can You Win Against <i>Japchae?</i>
-Can You Win Against <i>Japchae?</i>

388
00:14:28,234 --> 00:14:30,736
AN HOMAGE TO JONG-WON'S QUOTE,
"CAN YOU STOP ME?"

389
00:14:31,270 --> 00:14:32,905
THE ORIGINATOR
GETS TORTURED(?) FOREVER

390
00:14:32,972 --> 00:14:34,907
You already mentioned
that you loved <i>japchae,</i>

391
00:14:34,974 --> 00:14:36,775
but what did you mean by this?

392
00:14:36,842 --> 00:14:40,012
As I mentioned before,
I really love <i>japchae.</i>

393
00:14:40,079 --> 00:14:43,515
So I wanted to ask you for a dish
that's even better.

394
00:14:43,582 --> 00:14:46,452
-That'd be nice. With glass noodles.
-Win against <i>japchae?</i>

395
00:14:46,518 --> 00:14:49,655
You want something that'll make you say,
"This is better than <i>japchae,</i>" right?

396
00:14:49,722 --> 00:14:51,857
What about the ingredients?
It's made with glass noodles.

397
00:14:51,924 --> 00:14:55,060
-Please use glass noodles.
-By using glass noodles?

398
00:14:55,127 --> 00:14:56,462
-A glass noodle dish.
-Yes.

399
00:14:56,528 --> 00:14:58,530
Do you only like <i>japchae</i>
or glass noodles themselves?

400
00:14:58,597 --> 00:14:59,999
I think I like glass noodles.

401
00:15:00,065 --> 00:15:03,102
I also like making <i>tteokbokki</i> with those.

402
00:15:03,168 --> 00:15:05,204
-I see. Glass noodles-<i>bokki.</i>
-With glass noodles.

403
00:15:05,271 --> 00:15:07,039
Something that's better than <i>japchae.</i>

404
00:15:07,106 --> 00:15:08,274
What's the next order?

405
00:15:08,340 --> 00:15:09,909
What does Jun-myun want?

406
00:15:09,975 --> 00:15:12,678
It'd Be Nice If Someone Gave Me
the Fine Dining Experience.

407
00:15:12,745 --> 00:15:14,280
-You never had a chance.
-No.

408
00:15:14,346 --> 00:15:17,182
The best chefs in Korea are here,

409
00:15:17,249 --> 00:15:19,685
so I want to get
that fine dining experience.

410
00:15:19,752 --> 00:15:21,754
-The runner is already decided, then.
-Right?

411
00:15:21,820 --> 00:15:23,989
I'll enjoy whatever you make.

412
00:15:24,056 --> 00:15:26,225
The names remind me
of <i>Culinary Class Wars 2.</i>

413
00:15:26,292 --> 00:15:29,728
Yes, it has recently become
my favorite program.

414
00:15:29,795 --> 00:15:33,132
Just sitting here makes my heart race.

415
00:15:33,198 --> 00:15:34,700
Let's see who'll do which round.

416
00:15:34,767 --> 00:15:36,902
There are four people
who haven't cooked last week,

417
00:15:36,969 --> 00:15:40,205
Poong, Jong-won, Nam-no and Sung-jun.

418
00:15:40,272 --> 00:15:42,007
Judging by the title,

419
00:15:42,074 --> 00:15:44,710
I feel like I should take up
Can You Win Against <i>Japchae?</i>

420
00:15:44,777 --> 00:15:46,345
You said that.

421
00:15:46,412 --> 00:15:48,013
HIS PERSONAL BUZZWORD

422
00:15:48,080 --> 00:15:50,015
But she wants the fine dining experience,

423
00:15:50,082 --> 00:15:53,118
-so I want to give her what she wants.
-It's what you do.

424
00:15:53,185 --> 00:15:54,954
It'd Be Nice If Someone Gave Me
the Fine Dining Experience.

425
00:15:55,020 --> 00:15:57,189
-Hey.
-Jong-won is in,

426
00:15:57,256 --> 00:15:59,591
the most buzzworthy man at the moment.

427
00:15:59,658 --> 00:16:01,193
I'm in.

428
00:16:01,694 --> 00:16:02,861
Yes, Sung-jun?

429
00:16:02,928 --> 00:16:06,999
I'm someone who always sticks around
next to the biggest star.

430
00:16:07,066 --> 00:16:08,400
SLY SUNG-JUN,
ALWAYS AFTER A STAR

431
00:16:08,467 --> 00:16:10,669
It'd Be Nice If Someone Gave Me
the Fine Dining Experience.

432
00:16:10,736 --> 00:16:12,571
Are you joining the round
to beat Jong-won?

433
00:16:12,638 --> 00:16:14,740
-I must win while he's the hottest…
-Right.

434
00:16:14,807 --> 00:16:16,642
-…to steal his thunder.
-That's true.

435
00:16:16,709 --> 00:16:18,844
After all, you were the winner
of <i>Culinary Class Wars 1.</i>

436
00:16:18,911 --> 00:16:21,313
Oh, that's right! You won that season.
I remember now.

437
00:16:21,380 --> 00:16:22,915
-First place isn't so bad.
-Right, I won.

438
00:16:22,982 --> 00:16:24,483
-Yes, you did.
-You didn't do so badly.

439
00:16:24,984 --> 00:16:27,453
THE WINNER OF CCW 1
VERSUS THE MOST BUZZWORTHY MAN

440
00:16:27,519 --> 00:16:29,788
Sung-jun takes the fine dining round.

441
00:16:29,855 --> 00:16:31,824
-Wait a second.
-It's a big match.

442
00:16:32,224 --> 00:16:33,625
IT'S ME, POONGPHOBIA

443
00:16:33,692 --> 00:16:35,327
-It's now decided automatically.
-It is.

444
00:16:35,394 --> 00:16:36,695
Answer us!

445
00:16:36,762 --> 00:16:38,998
THE FIRST TIME HE WON…

446
00:16:39,431 --> 00:16:41,433
I JUST THOUGHT
HE WAS A LUCKY WEBTOON ARTIST

447
00:16:42,067 --> 00:16:43,702
THEN CAME THE SECOND WIN…

448
00:16:43,769 --> 00:16:45,671
AND THE THIRD…

449
00:16:45,938 --> 00:16:48,140
I LOST AGAINST HIM
4 TIMES IN A ROW

450
00:16:48,207 --> 00:16:49,875
He continues to suffer from Poongphobia!

451
00:16:50,876 --> 00:16:52,011
The <i>japchae</i> round is already set.

452
00:16:52,077 --> 00:16:53,479
You're right.

453
00:16:53,545 --> 00:16:56,148
-You should've called first dibs.
-Poong will win again.

454
00:16:56,215 --> 00:16:58,684
-You should defeat him this year.
-Poong and Nam-no are up.

455
00:16:58,751 --> 00:17:00,185
-It has begun.
-You must defeat him.

456
00:17:00,252 --> 00:17:01,553
Yes, you must beat him.

457
00:17:01,620 --> 00:17:03,589
-I'll take down Satan.
-Right?

458
00:17:03,655 --> 00:17:05,457
You must break that jinx.

459
00:17:05,524 --> 00:17:07,059
-He dyed his hair too.
-Exactly.

460
00:17:07,393 --> 00:17:08,360
SHAKING IN FEAR

461
00:17:08,427 --> 00:17:10,295
All right, then.
Let us begin the first round,

462
00:17:10,362 --> 00:17:14,099
the 15-minute cook-off
between Poong and Nam-no!

463
00:17:17,269 --> 00:17:21,640
<i>This is the first round</i>
<i>fought with Jun-myun's ingredients.</i>

464
00:17:21,707 --> 00:17:26,245
Chef Yoon Nam-no,
who shudders at the sound of Poong's name,

465
00:17:26,311 --> 00:17:30,149
versus Webtoon Artist Kim Poong,
who finds the sound

466
00:17:30,215 --> 00:17:32,718
of Nam-no's name so sweet to his ears.

467
00:17:32,785 --> 00:17:34,820
They're like natural enemies.

468
00:17:34,887 --> 00:17:36,355
Like a fly and a lizard.

469
00:17:36,422 --> 00:17:37,956
Yes, just like that.

470
00:17:38,023 --> 00:17:39,925
-A fly?
-They're natural enemies.

471
00:17:39,992 --> 00:17:43,028
Lizards devour flies whenever they fly by.

472
00:17:43,095 --> 00:17:46,031
I hope Chef Nam-no overcomes
his fear of Poong.

473
00:17:46,098 --> 00:17:47,032
Chef Nam-no?

474
00:17:47,099 --> 00:17:49,168
Well, I recently dyed my hair.

475
00:17:49,234 --> 00:17:51,670
Today, I'll ram into him like a wild boar.

476
00:17:52,337 --> 00:17:53,872
-With a fresh heart.
-Oh, my.

477
00:17:53,939 --> 00:17:54,807
A black pig.

478
00:17:54,873 --> 00:17:56,375
-You two…
-A black pig?

479
00:17:56,442 --> 00:17:58,844
-A black pig or a wild boar?
-A black pig.

480
00:17:58,911 --> 00:18:01,413
Also, Poong is wearing an apron

481
00:18:01,480 --> 00:18:03,649
he got as a gift from Jong-won.

482
00:18:03,715 --> 00:18:05,184
It feels different on him.

483
00:18:05,250 --> 00:18:07,352
-Really? He gave it to you?
-Yes.

484
00:18:07,419 --> 00:18:09,988
I guess the two most buzzworthy men
exchange gifts.

485
00:18:10,055 --> 00:18:11,056
I guess we do.

486
00:18:11,123 --> 00:18:13,192
-It's not a big deal.
-Just between you two?

487
00:18:13,258 --> 00:18:14,927
They only want to hang out
with each other.

488
00:18:14,993 --> 00:18:17,262
-Yes, they do.
-Let's share some soda, then.

489
00:18:17,329 --> 00:18:20,099
Do you feel different in that apron?

490
00:18:20,165 --> 00:18:22,835
-People say clothes make the man.
-He looks elegant.

491
00:18:22,901 --> 00:18:25,604
So yes, I feel much calmer in this apron.

492
00:18:25,671 --> 00:18:26,839
-Do you?
-Yes.

493
00:18:26,905 --> 00:18:29,174
-Because Jong-won can keep his calm.
-Yes.

494
00:18:29,241 --> 00:18:31,076
You now have Jong-won's good energy

495
00:18:31,143 --> 00:18:33,312
on top of the fact
that Nam-no's your natural prey.

496
00:18:33,378 --> 00:18:35,047
You may easily get a star today.

497
00:18:35,114 --> 00:18:37,416
First of all, I'm hoping

498
00:18:37,483 --> 00:18:39,351
that Chef Nam-no uses

499
00:18:39,418 --> 00:18:40,452
this opportunity

500
00:18:40,519 --> 00:18:42,654
to step on me and fly higher.

501
00:18:42,721 --> 00:18:44,690
I want to see him fly freely.

502
00:18:44,756 --> 00:18:47,092
-He's wishing him well.
-I want him…

503
00:18:47,159 --> 00:18:48,627
-Wishing him well?
-…to overcome

504
00:18:48,694 --> 00:18:51,430
-his Poongphobia.
-He's not in a position to say that.

505
00:18:51,497 --> 00:18:54,867
The first round is titled,
"Can You Win Against <i>Japchae</i>?"

506
00:18:54,933 --> 00:18:56,802
Chef Nam-no is a guy

507
00:18:56,869 --> 00:18:58,871
who's nicknamed Noodles Nam-no.

508
00:18:58,937 --> 00:19:00,906
Noodles Nam-no or Yoon Nam Noodles.

509
00:19:00,973 --> 00:19:03,709
Or we can go, Park Jun Noodles Nam-no.

510
00:19:03,775 --> 00:19:07,379
Do you have anything you're looking for
in a glass noodle dish?

511
00:19:07,446 --> 00:19:09,548
Most glass noodles dishes
we think of are predictable,

512
00:19:09,615 --> 00:19:12,284
so I want something
that is far from cliché.

513
00:19:12,351 --> 00:19:14,486
That'll be the most decisive factor.

514
00:19:14,553 --> 00:19:15,521
Something extraordinary.

515
00:19:15,587 --> 00:19:17,723
You played the royal food taster

516
00:19:17,789 --> 00:19:20,259
-in <i>Bon Appétit, Your Majesty,</i> right?
-The royal taster.

517
00:19:20,325 --> 00:19:24,229
I'm sure she'll share
a critical assessment during the tasting.

518
00:19:25,063 --> 00:19:27,299
CHEF NAM-NO'S INGREDIENTS: GLASS NOODLES,
BEEF BRISKET, SQUID, CABBAGE, ZUCCHINI

519
00:19:27,366 --> 00:19:29,568
XO SAUCE, SHRIMP POWDER, BUTTER, KIMCHI,
PICKLING MELON, PERILLA OIL, DRIED SHRIMP

520
00:19:29,635 --> 00:19:31,436
My dish is called

521
00:19:31,503 --> 00:19:32,971
Binge Appétit, Your Majesty.

522
00:19:33,038 --> 00:19:34,907
-Binge Appétit, Your Majesty.
-Binge Appétit, Your Majesty.

523
00:19:34,973 --> 00:19:36,909
-And not <i>Bon Appétit, Your Majesty?</i>
-What?

524
00:19:36,975 --> 00:19:38,644
Binge Appétit, Your Majesty.

525
00:19:38,710 --> 00:19:41,580
I'll make Hong Kong-style fried noodles
that'll surpass <i>japchae.</i>

526
00:19:42,514 --> 00:19:44,349
-Hong Kong-style fried noodles?
-Hong Kong-style fried noodles?

527
00:19:44,416 --> 00:19:46,051
And on the side,

528
00:19:46,118 --> 00:19:50,289
I'll serve a salad
made with pickling melon and kimchi.

529
00:19:50,355 --> 00:19:51,723
The moment you see the dish,

530
00:19:51,790 --> 00:19:54,660
you'll be able to binge just like me.

531
00:19:54,726 --> 00:19:56,628
It's a glass noodle dish
better than <i>japchae.</i>

532
00:19:56,695 --> 00:19:58,297
-That was convincing.
-Binge Appétit, Your Majesty.

533
00:19:58,363 --> 00:19:59,498
-All right.
-A glass noodle dish.

534
00:20:00,332 --> 00:20:02,568
WEBTOON ARTIST POONG'S INGREDIENTS:
GLASS NOODLE, BEEF BRISKET

535
00:20:02,634 --> 00:20:04,836
BOILED TRIPE, KIMCHI, CHILI SEED,
SCALLION, UDON SOY SAUCE, CRUSHED PEANUT

536
00:20:04,903 --> 00:20:08,106
Webtoon Artist Poong is up against him,
and what are you making?

537
00:20:08,173 --> 00:20:10,242
It's based on Chinese cuisine.

538
00:20:10,309 --> 00:20:11,843
Her kimchi was so delicious,

539
00:20:11,910 --> 00:20:13,912
so I'm going to mix that into my broth

540
00:20:13,979 --> 00:20:16,048
and top it with flavored oil.
But it's not a soup dish.

541
00:20:16,114 --> 00:20:18,317
You'll eat just the noodles
with a bit of soupy sauce.

542
00:20:18,383 --> 00:20:20,719
It's a Chinese-style glass noodle dish.

543
00:20:20,786 --> 00:20:22,421
Also,

544
00:20:22,487 --> 00:20:25,657
-there's a Chinese dessert called <i>sachima.</i>
<i>-Sachima?</i>

545
00:20:25,724 --> 00:20:27,059
It's called <i>sachima,</i>

546
00:20:27,125 --> 00:20:29,795
and it's similar to <i>gangjeong</i>,
Rice Krispies-style treats.

547
00:20:29,861 --> 00:20:31,129
I'll deep-fry the noodles,

548
00:20:31,196 --> 00:20:34,032
mix them with starch syrup or sugar,

549
00:20:34,099 --> 00:20:37,836
and harden them just like <i>gangjeong</i>.

550
00:20:37,903 --> 00:20:39,338
THAT SOUNDS DELICIOUS

551
00:20:39,404 --> 00:20:40,772
What's the main dish, then?

552
00:20:40,839 --> 00:20:42,341
The first…

553
00:20:42,407 --> 00:20:43,342
Both.

554
00:20:43,408 --> 00:20:44,509
Whichever that turns out well.

555
00:20:44,576 --> 00:20:46,178
The one that turns out better
is my main dish.

556
00:20:46,245 --> 00:20:48,547
-Yes.
-The one that turns out better.

557
00:20:48,614 --> 00:20:50,749
-That always seems to be the case.
-Yes.

558
00:20:50,816 --> 00:20:55,120
And now, we're going to begin
the cook-off just for Jun-myun.

559
00:20:55,187 --> 00:20:57,956
I really have to break
my four-game losing streak.

560
00:20:58,023 --> 00:21:00,759
Determined to devour Poong
in this new year,

561
00:21:00,826 --> 00:21:03,695
the binge eater of the show,
Chef Yoon Nam-no is up.

562
00:21:03,762 --> 00:21:06,331
Determined to beat just Nam-no
in this new year,

563
00:21:06,398 --> 00:21:09,401
the picky fighter of the show,
Webtoon Artist Poong is also up.

564
00:21:09,468 --> 00:21:10,636
What are you beating him with?

565
00:21:10,702 --> 00:21:15,073
Will his Poongphobia
finally come to an end?

566
00:21:15,140 --> 00:21:17,909
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

567
00:21:18,910 --> 00:21:21,280
It's an important round for Nam-no.

568
00:21:22,147 --> 00:21:23,415
SALUTE!

569
00:21:23,949 --> 00:21:25,751
It's an important round for Nam-no.

570
00:21:25,817 --> 00:21:27,252
-Please.
-Right?

571
00:21:27,319 --> 00:21:28,387
He lost four times in a row.

572
00:21:28,453 --> 00:21:29,521
He did.

573
00:21:29,788 --> 00:21:31,123
1. GRIND GARLIC

574
00:21:31,189 --> 00:21:33,125
-What's he grinding?
-Garlic, I think.

575
00:21:34,026 --> 00:21:35,227
But she had crushed garlic. Why?

576
00:21:35,294 --> 00:21:36,928
This adds a better aroma.

577
00:21:36,995 --> 00:21:38,563
Are you using lots of garlic?

578
00:21:38,630 --> 00:21:41,733
-Why is he using so much garlic?
-Look at all the garlic.

579
00:21:41,800 --> 00:21:44,336
-He's using so much garlic.
-Isn't that too much?

580
00:21:44,403 --> 00:21:45,904
Wouldn't it be too spicy?

581
00:21:45,971 --> 00:21:47,773
No, I'll fry it and make it savory.

582
00:21:47,839 --> 00:21:49,808
-That's a lot of garlic.
-That's a lot.

583
00:21:49,875 --> 00:21:51,043
That's a huge amount of garlic.

584
00:21:51,109 --> 00:21:54,579
-Both contestants have no stars this year.
-No.

585
00:21:54,646 --> 00:21:57,416
In that while, Eun-yeong already got two.

586
00:21:57,482 --> 00:21:58,884
Webtoon Artist Poong is…

587
00:21:59,384 --> 00:22:01,086
ALL IS SAID AND DONE, BUT

588
00:22:01,653 --> 00:22:03,488
-Isn't that too spicy?
-I knew it. Chili oil.

589
00:22:03,555 --> 00:22:05,657
-He does the same thing in every episode.
-Chili oil.

590
00:22:05,724 --> 00:22:07,459
<i>It's always the same shot.</i>

591
00:22:07,526 --> 00:22:09,227
Well, I guess it doesn't really matter.

592
00:22:09,294 --> 00:22:11,963
-People may think this is a rerun.
-Right?

593
00:22:12,030 --> 00:22:13,899
But he said
the fridge owners are different,

594
00:22:13,965 --> 00:22:15,567
-so who would care?
-He keeps ratting on him.

595
00:22:15,634 --> 00:22:18,170
He does.
He's the guy who rats on everyone.

596
00:22:18,837 --> 00:22:20,105
Chili seeds.

597
00:22:20,172 --> 00:22:22,474
It's different today
because I'm using chili seeds.

598
00:22:22,541 --> 00:22:24,176
He added chili seeds today.

599
00:22:24,242 --> 00:22:26,011
It'll make this extra savory.

600
00:22:26,078 --> 00:22:28,246
He's adding chili seeds today.

601
00:22:28,313 --> 00:22:31,216
-He does make really good chili oil.
-He does.

602
00:22:31,483 --> 00:22:32,684
WHAT ABOUT NAM-NO?

603
00:22:33,318 --> 00:22:35,754
CHOPPING NAPA CABBAGE!

604
00:22:38,256 --> 00:22:39,324
He's removing the zucchini core.

605
00:22:39,391 --> 00:22:42,194
Nam-no must do a great job today
and win this round.

606
00:22:42,260 --> 00:22:45,564
If you want to see
a great result in this season,

607
00:22:45,630 --> 00:22:47,666
you must get over Poong.

608
00:22:47,733 --> 00:22:49,167
-He must overcome his phobia.
-Please.

609
00:22:49,234 --> 00:22:52,137
-You can't lose five times in a row.
-No, that I really can't do.

610
00:22:52,204 --> 00:22:54,139
-He must break his losing streak.
-Yes.

611
00:22:54,206 --> 00:22:55,107
CHOPPED ZUCCHINI
GOES ON THE TRAY TOO!

612
00:22:55,173 --> 00:22:56,408
Those must be for the noodles.

613
00:22:56,742 --> 00:22:58,110
NEXT, GREEN ONION!

614
00:22:58,510 --> 00:22:59,578
CIRCULAR SHAPES

615
00:22:59,745 --> 00:23:00,779
DIAGONAL CUTS

616
00:23:00,846 --> 00:23:02,214
JULIENNING

617
00:23:02,781 --> 00:23:04,883
-He prepped so much.
-Right?

618
00:23:05,717 --> 00:23:06,952
When it comes to glass noodles…

619
00:23:07,018 --> 00:23:10,956
-Yes?
-…some like it firm and some like it soft.

620
00:23:11,022 --> 00:23:13,058
-I like bouncy ones.
-Bouncy noodles.

621
00:23:13,125 --> 00:23:15,627
I don't like overcooked noodles.

622
00:23:16,228 --> 00:23:17,462
HEARS HER AND SETS UP THE TIMER

623
00:23:18,029 --> 00:23:18,964
POONG PREPS TOO!

624
00:23:19,030 --> 00:23:20,132
Are those green onions?

625
00:23:20,198 --> 00:23:21,533
-Scallions.
-Scallions.

626
00:23:21,600 --> 00:23:23,101
I've never seen anyone cut it like that.

627
00:23:23,168 --> 00:23:24,903
…CUTTING THE SAME SPOT?

628
00:23:24,970 --> 00:23:28,206
The cutting sound is the same
as that of other chefs,

629
00:23:28,273 --> 00:23:29,608
but the pieces aren't uniform.

630
00:23:29,674 --> 00:23:31,510
It's not just that.

631
00:23:31,576 --> 00:23:34,312
A few pieces on the bottom
got mushed instead of getting cut.

632
00:23:34,780 --> 00:23:36,615
FRANTIC

633
00:23:38,216 --> 00:23:41,119
CHOPS CHILI PEPPERS
IN THE SAME MANNER

634
00:23:41,753 --> 00:23:43,188
Crushed garlic.

635
00:23:43,255 --> 00:23:44,723
Crushed garlic! There it is.

636
00:23:44,923 --> 00:23:46,124
SCALLIONS, CHILI PEPPERS
& CRUSHED GARLIC

637
00:23:46,191 --> 00:23:47,192
Okay.

638
00:23:47,592 --> 00:23:50,028
1. MIX CHILI OIL WITH THE VEGGIES
AND MAKE FLAVORED OIL

639
00:23:50,095 --> 00:23:52,097
He poured oil on top of everything.

640
00:23:52,164 --> 00:23:54,699
Today's chili oil looks unique.

641
00:23:54,766 --> 00:23:57,269
Yes, I made flavored oil with chili oil.

642
00:23:58,270 --> 00:23:59,871
He came a long way.

643
00:23:59,938 --> 00:24:02,040
Yes, Poong is improving.

644
00:24:02,107 --> 00:24:03,975
-He puts chili seeds…
-Chili seeds.

645
00:24:04,042 --> 00:24:06,311
…into a tea bag to make chili broth.

646
00:24:06,378 --> 00:24:07,512
Really?

647
00:24:07,579 --> 00:24:08,914
He previously said

648
00:24:08,980 --> 00:24:11,316
adding chili seeds to soup dishes

649
00:24:11,383 --> 00:24:12,918
deepens the flavor by a lot.

650
00:24:12,984 --> 00:24:14,419
-Soy sauce.
-Yes.

651
00:24:14,486 --> 00:24:16,421
He doesn't even measure it.

652
00:24:16,488 --> 00:24:19,357
Can you tell us
the ratio between water and soy sauce?

653
00:24:19,424 --> 00:24:20,792
Water to soy sauce.

654
00:24:20,859 --> 00:24:22,828
You can find it on the Internet.

655
00:24:23,295 --> 00:24:24,729
RECOMMENDS 9OOGLING

656
00:24:24,796 --> 00:24:26,598
You're supposed to tell us.

657
00:24:26,665 --> 00:24:28,767
You have 11 minutes left.

658
00:24:29,034 --> 00:24:29,935
ALREADY?

659
00:24:30,502 --> 00:24:32,704
-Four minutes have passed.
-One second.

660
00:24:32,771 --> 00:24:34,172
She had XO sauce?

661
00:24:34,906 --> 00:24:35,974
XO sauce.

662
00:24:37,108 --> 00:24:37,943
Cooking wine.

663
00:24:38,510 --> 00:24:39,478
And that much soy sauce?

664
00:24:40,312 --> 00:24:42,747
-Sugar.
-Are you making the sauce?

665
00:24:42,814 --> 00:24:44,049
You're right.

666
00:24:44,115 --> 00:24:46,852
He must be making it sweet
in Hong Kong style.

667
00:24:46,918 --> 00:24:48,487
It'll be spicy, sweet, and salty,

668
00:24:48,553 --> 00:24:49,421
and exploding with umami.

669
00:24:49,988 --> 00:24:51,756
-That's nice.
-For the noodles.

670
00:24:51,823 --> 00:24:53,291
<i>Today, I'll ram into him like a wild boar.</i>

671
00:24:53,358 --> 00:24:54,559
A BOAR WITH BROKEN BRAKES

672
00:24:54,626 --> 00:24:56,061
Eggs?

673
00:24:56,127 --> 00:24:57,929
Nam-no uses lots of eggs.

674
00:24:58,630 --> 00:24:59,998
-Three eggs.
-What's that for?

675
00:25:00,065 --> 00:25:01,132
I'm making scrambled eggs.

676
00:25:01,199 --> 00:25:03,268
-You need five eggs for that?
-Five eggs.

677
00:25:03,835 --> 00:25:05,470
Eat your eggs in odd numbers, so five.

678
00:25:05,537 --> 00:25:07,172
NAM-NO'S PHILOSOPHY:
START WITH 5 EGGS

679
00:25:07,239 --> 00:25:08,907
-What's it for?
-Was he to make 20 servings?

680
00:25:08,974 --> 00:25:10,275
He's making a huge serving.

681
00:25:10,342 --> 00:25:11,943
He's mixing egg whites and yolks.

682
00:25:12,511 --> 00:25:13,378
SHRIMP POWDER

683
00:25:13,445 --> 00:25:14,713
And the soy sauce?

684
00:25:14,779 --> 00:25:16,781
-He's seasoning the eggs.
-It's going in the eggs.

685
00:25:16,848 --> 00:25:19,451
You just added soy sauce
and salt to the eggs, right?

686
00:25:19,518 --> 00:25:20,685
Yes.

687
00:25:20,752 --> 00:25:22,454
And that much butter?

688
00:25:22,521 --> 00:25:24,589
That's how he's cooking the eggs?

689
00:25:24,656 --> 00:25:27,292
-He's making scrambled eggs.
-Scrambled eggs.

690
00:25:27,359 --> 00:25:28,960
-It looks good.
-Doesn't it?

691
00:25:29,361 --> 00:25:31,396
BOAR NAM-NO CHARGES
WITH FULL FORCE

692
00:25:31,463 --> 00:25:32,297
It does look good.

693
00:25:32,764 --> 00:25:34,533
MEANWHILE, THE GLASS NOODLE
QUEEN GRABS THE NOODLES

694
00:25:34,799 --> 00:25:35,634
BREAKS

695
00:25:38,203 --> 00:25:39,404
GROWING GLASS NOODLES

696
00:25:39,471 --> 00:25:41,273
-They're rising.
-They're rising.

697
00:25:41,339 --> 00:25:43,441
-They're rising.
-The noodles are rising.

698
00:25:43,508 --> 00:25:45,644
-It looks cool when it rises.
-It does.

699
00:25:45,710 --> 00:25:47,746
-They look like fried snacks.
-So that happens.

700
00:25:47,812 --> 00:25:49,614
Are you making <i>sachimi?</i>

701
00:25:49,681 --> 00:25:51,683
<i>-Sachima.</i>
<i>-Sachima.</i>

702
00:25:51,750 --> 00:25:53,518
-Don't get it wrong, man.
<i>-Sachima.</i>

703
00:25:54,553 --> 00:25:56,288
<i>-Sachima.</i>
-Don't get it wrong!

704
00:25:56,354 --> 00:25:57,422
-Chef Eun-yeong.
-Yes?

705
00:25:57,489 --> 00:25:59,257
Is that how you make <i>sachima?</i>

706
00:25:59,324 --> 00:26:02,093
I have no idea.
I don't know what method he's using.

707
