957
00:34:28,666 --> 00:34:32,003
-What do you need? Ring the bell first.
-Five. Four. Three.

958
00:34:32,070 --> 00:34:34,072
It's better to finish first!

959
00:34:34,138 --> 00:34:35,573
Nam-no is done!

960
00:34:35,640 --> 00:34:37,708
Sesame seeds. Okay. Ring the bell!

961
00:34:37,775 --> 00:34:39,944
-Ringing!
-I have to serve this.

962
00:34:40,011 --> 00:34:43,114
-Nam-no finishes first, followed by Poong.
-Hey, wait.

963
00:34:43,181 --> 00:34:46,050
It looks like a decent Sichuan dish.

964
00:34:46,117 --> 00:34:47,585
This looks like <i>kimchi-jjigae,</i>

965
00:34:47,652 --> 00:34:49,387
but this one looks like Chinese cuisine.

966
00:34:49,454 --> 00:34:51,456
-It turned into one.
-That's so weird.

967
00:34:51,522 --> 00:34:53,925
And he made the snack
look like a bowl of rice.

968
00:34:54,592 --> 00:34:57,228
A LITTLE TASTE…

969
00:34:58,863 --> 00:34:59,997
LAUGHS AT THE SAME TIME

970
00:35:00,531 --> 00:35:02,266
WHY DID THE TWO CHEFS
LAUGH OUT LOUD?

971
00:35:02,333 --> 00:35:05,203
In a word, they're amazing.

972
00:35:05,269 --> 00:35:06,637
Wow.

973
00:35:06,704 --> 00:35:10,675
And now, the noodle dishes
for Jun-myun are served.

974
00:35:10,741 --> 00:35:13,911
The two did their best
to put these together.

975
00:35:13,978 --> 00:35:16,347
I have so much respect for the chefs here.

976
00:35:16,414 --> 00:35:18,182
You all are the best.

977
00:35:18,249 --> 00:35:20,084
No other show is as cool as this one.

978
00:35:20,151 --> 00:35:21,185
THE GREAT SHOWMEN

979
00:35:21,252 --> 00:35:23,020
-I'm so glad I came.
-I see.

980
00:35:23,087 --> 00:35:24,288
You were all so wonderful.

981
00:35:24,355 --> 00:35:26,457
They were.

982
00:35:26,524 --> 00:35:29,193
Please try Chef Nam-no's dish,
Binge Appétit, Your Majesty.

983
00:35:30,928 --> 00:35:33,664
A MOUND OF FLUFFY EGGS
ON GLASS NOODLES

984
00:35:34,232 --> 00:35:36,901
HONG KONG-STYLE FRIED NOODLES

985
00:35:36,968 --> 00:35:39,003
WITH PICKLED MELON AND KIMCHI SALAD

986
00:35:39,504 --> 00:35:42,573
CHEF YOON NAM-NO'S
BINGE APPÉTIT, YOUR MAJESTY

987
00:35:42,640 --> 00:35:44,609
He made a huge serving.

988
00:35:44,675 --> 00:35:46,644
It looks good.

989
00:35:46,711 --> 00:35:49,447
-Try it with the egg and green onion.
-Everything.

990
00:35:49,514 --> 00:35:51,482
Her favorite Korean dish is <i>japchae.</i>

991
00:35:51,549 --> 00:35:52,884
May I try just the egg first?

992
00:35:52,950 --> 00:35:53,851
Sure.

993
00:35:57,321 --> 00:35:59,957
-It's so soft.
-It's soft?

994
00:36:00,024 --> 00:36:01,893
-Is it salty?
-He seemed to use lots of soy sauce,

995
00:36:01,959 --> 00:36:03,828
-but it isn't overly salty.
-It's not?

996
00:36:03,895 --> 00:36:06,597
-I love how it's seasoned.
-I thought it'd be salty, but it wasn't.

997
00:36:07,398 --> 00:36:08,599
She loves <i>japchae,</i>

998
00:36:08,666 --> 00:36:10,801
-so she must've had lots of glass noodles.
-Right?

999
00:36:10,868 --> 00:36:13,404
-She said <i>japchae </i>was her favorite dish!
-<i>Japchae!</i>

1000
00:36:13,471 --> 00:36:15,473
-Can You Win Against <i>Japchae?</i>
-She's grabbing that much?

1001
00:36:15,540 --> 00:36:17,041
NOODLES GOING IN

1002
00:36:17,108 --> 00:36:17,975
MMM

1003
00:36:18,476 --> 00:36:19,410
It must be easy to eat.

1004
00:36:19,477 --> 00:36:20,845
The texture is important.

1005
00:36:20,912 --> 00:36:23,614
Was it cooked to your liking?

1006
00:36:23,681 --> 00:36:24,715
Yes!

1007
00:36:25,416 --> 00:36:26,651
COUGHING

1008
00:36:27,451 --> 00:36:28,653
KINDLY GIVES HER TISSUE

1009
00:36:28,719 --> 00:36:30,454
You might choke, so have some water.

1010
00:36:30,521 --> 00:36:31,622
I will.

1011
00:36:31,689 --> 00:36:33,424
She seems happy.

1012
00:36:33,491 --> 00:36:34,992
I'm happy too.

1013
00:36:35,059 --> 00:36:37,061
Like I said, I really love <i>japchae,</i>

1014
00:36:37,128 --> 00:36:39,630
and the texture is exactly how I like it.

1015
00:36:40,565 --> 00:36:42,733
-The texture is made to your liking.
-Yes.

1016
00:36:44,168 --> 00:36:45,036
READY FOR ONE MORE

1017
00:36:45,102 --> 00:36:46,637
Let me have another bite.

1018
00:36:46,704 --> 00:36:48,506
-You can finish it.
-You can have it all.

1019
00:36:48,573 --> 00:36:50,274
It's really good.

1020
00:36:50,341 --> 00:36:52,443
-There won't be enough for us.
-He has more.

1021
00:36:52,510 --> 00:36:54,378
He'll make more.

1022
00:36:54,445 --> 00:36:56,180
-They'll save some for you.
-Just for you.

1023
00:36:56,247 --> 00:36:57,682
There are a lot of noodles.

1024
00:36:58,182 --> 00:36:59,584
IT'S QUITE A LOT

1025
00:37:00,017 --> 00:37:01,285
HERE GOES
JUN-MYUN THE NOODLE LOVER

1026
00:37:01,352 --> 00:37:03,454
-We won't get any.
-She won't leave any for Young-ok.

1027
00:37:04,422 --> 00:37:07,058
-She must love glass noodles.
-She's enjoying it so much.

1028
00:37:07,124 --> 00:37:08,826
Was this Hong Kong-style fried noodles?

1029
00:37:08,893 --> 00:37:10,895
Yes, it's totally in Hong Kong style.

1030
00:37:10,962 --> 00:37:13,164
-It's really good.
-It's usually made with egg noodles,

1031
00:37:13,231 --> 00:37:17,235
but there aren't any,
so I used glass noodles, which you like.

1032
00:37:17,301 --> 00:37:19,537
-It was a reinterpretation.
-When I make <i>japchae,</i>

1033
00:37:19,604 --> 00:37:22,540
I get tired
trying to add more ingredients,

1034
00:37:22,607 --> 00:37:25,042
but these are already delicious enough.

1035
00:37:25,109 --> 00:37:27,078
Let me try the pickling melon.

1036
00:37:27,144 --> 00:37:28,446
What was that one?

1037
00:37:28,512 --> 00:37:30,348
It's dried shrimp and… Well, it's a salad.

1038
00:37:30,414 --> 00:37:32,216
I made it

1039
00:37:32,283 --> 00:37:35,353
with <i>mukeunji,</i> pickling melon,
dried shrimp, and perilla oil.

1040
00:37:35,419 --> 00:37:37,121
His voice is so high right now.

1041
00:37:37,521 --> 00:37:39,156
HOO, HA

1042
00:37:39,223 --> 00:37:40,591
Did you serve it as a side dish?

1043
00:37:40,658 --> 00:37:41,826
Yes, a refresher.

1044
00:37:42,093 --> 00:37:43,261
HE'S SO FUNNY

1045
00:37:43,327 --> 00:37:47,598
A bite of this helps clean out my mouth.

1046
00:37:48,199 --> 00:37:49,033
STILL HILARIOUS

1047
00:37:49,100 --> 00:37:51,902
-It's good.
-So it cleans your palate.

1048
00:37:52,303 --> 00:37:54,105
IT TAKES HIM A WHILE
TO GET OVER IT

1049
00:37:54,171 --> 00:37:56,173
-He added squid too, right?
-He did.

1050
00:37:57,108 --> 00:37:57,942
MMM

1051
00:37:58,009 --> 00:37:59,010
MMM

1052
00:37:59,076 --> 00:38:01,112
It has a nice chew to it,

1053
00:38:01,178 --> 00:38:03,014
-and it's been cooked well.
-Please.

1054
00:38:03,881 --> 00:38:05,082
Let me have another bite.

1055
00:38:05,850 --> 00:38:08,319
-You can finish it.
-Eat it all.

1056
00:38:08,386 --> 00:38:12,290
The way you season your food
works perfectly with me.

1057
00:38:12,356 --> 00:38:13,557
It's seasoned perfectly.

1058
00:38:13,624 --> 00:38:16,794
-We thought it'd be too salty.
-That's my sis!

1059
00:38:16,861 --> 00:38:17,928
But she said it wasn't.

1060
00:38:17,995 --> 00:38:19,563
He threw in some soy sauce at the end.

1061
00:38:19,630 --> 00:38:21,499
-It's not salty.
-It's not?

1062
00:38:21,565 --> 00:38:23,100
It's so good.

1063
00:38:23,167 --> 00:38:26,003
Was it good enough to beat <i>japchae?</i>

1064
00:38:26,070 --> 00:38:27,405
-It was.
-It was?

1065
00:38:27,972 --> 00:38:31,042
WILL HE FINALLY BREAK FREE
FROM POONGPHOBIA?

1066
00:38:31,108 --> 00:38:32,543
Next up, Kim Poong.

1067
00:38:32,610 --> 00:38:34,578
-So?
-This is Poong's dish.

1068
00:38:35,479 --> 00:38:38,149
FLOATING CHILI OIL

1069
00:38:38,883 --> 00:38:41,886
ON TOP OF POONG'S STYLE GLASS
NOODLE DISH MADE WITH KIMCHI

1070
00:38:41,952 --> 00:38:42,853
AND SACHIMA!

1071
00:38:43,954 --> 00:38:46,991
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S
GLASS NOODLE QUEEN

1072
00:38:47,058 --> 00:38:48,359
My gosh.

1073
00:38:48,426 --> 00:38:50,628
-What is this?
-That wasn't the snack, but rice.

1074
00:38:50,695 --> 00:38:52,396
-It looks like a bowl of rice.
-That's odd.

1075
00:38:52,463 --> 00:38:55,032
-How did he do that?
-It looks like a big bowl of rice.

1076
00:38:55,099 --> 00:38:57,668
The soup has a thick layer of oil,

1077
00:38:57,735 --> 00:38:59,837
so you aren't supposed to have the soup.

1078
00:38:59,904 --> 00:39:02,139
It's already absorbed by the noodles,

1079
00:39:02,206 --> 00:39:04,308
So just eat the noodles
with your chopsticks.

1080
00:39:04,375 --> 00:39:06,410
-Like hot pot.
-Just scoop out the noodles.

1081
00:39:06,477 --> 00:39:09,046
My leftover <i>jjamppong</i> and rice
look just like that one.

1082
00:39:09,113 --> 00:39:10,181
LOOKS LIKE THAT?

1083
00:39:10,848 --> 00:39:12,883
There's no <i>jjamppong</i> that looks like mine.

1084
00:39:12,950 --> 00:39:15,753
There's a Chinese dish called <i>suan la fen,</i>

1085
00:39:15,820 --> 00:39:19,223
which is hot and sour noodles.

1086
00:39:19,290 --> 00:39:22,727
<i>I think he recreated that flavor</i>
<i>by adding sour kimchi</i>

1087
00:39:22,793 --> 00:39:24,895
to the spicy chili oil.

1088
00:39:25,696 --> 00:39:27,865
-It was based on something.
-Right?

1089
00:39:27,932 --> 00:39:29,333
It wasn't random.

1090
00:39:30,000 --> 00:39:31,135
That looks good too.

1091
00:39:31,202 --> 00:39:32,703
-Look at the color.
-This is important.

1092
00:39:32,770 --> 00:39:34,438
-It looks nice.
-My mouth is watering.

1093
00:39:34,505 --> 00:39:36,140
-Have the noodles gotten soggy?
-And fried noodles.

1094
00:39:36,207 --> 00:39:38,342
It's different
from Nam-no's glass noodle dish.

1095
00:39:39,143 --> 00:39:39,977
SLURP

1096
00:39:40,911 --> 00:39:42,279
I wonder what it's like.

1097
00:39:45,616 --> 00:39:46,984
NODS

1098
00:39:47,051 --> 00:39:49,019
-It's an emergency.
-Nam-no, it's an emergency.

1099
00:39:49,086 --> 00:39:50,755
-An emergency.
-Will Nam-no lose again?

1100
00:39:50,821 --> 00:39:53,324
-I hate seeing the same pattern!
-Is it good?

1101
00:39:53,391 --> 00:39:56,360
This is so peculiar.
How did he create this flavor?

1102
00:39:56,427 --> 00:39:58,696
-Wow.
-Do you like the texture?

1103
00:39:58,763 --> 00:40:01,432
-It's wonderful.
-Is it bouncy enough? Is it spicy?

1104
00:40:01,499 --> 00:40:02,333
It's not too spicy.

1105
00:40:02,400 --> 00:40:06,504
A thick layer of oil will keep
the noodles firm without getting soggy.

1106
00:40:06,570 --> 00:40:08,305
-Wow.
-It's fine even after some time.

1107
00:40:08,372 --> 00:40:09,974
-He knows that?
-It's not too spicy.

1108
00:40:10,040 --> 00:40:11,942
-He's like a real chef.
-I love the texture too.

1109
00:40:12,009 --> 00:40:13,411
-I see.
-The tripe looks so good.

1110
00:40:13,477 --> 00:40:14,779
-Let me try a piece.
-Sure.

1111
00:40:14,845 --> 00:40:17,081
Why do your dishes all look much better?

1112
00:40:17,548 --> 00:40:18,582
IT'S BECAUSE
SHE'S ENJOYING IT A LOT

1113
00:40:18,649 --> 00:40:20,017
Last week's chefs,
look back on yourselves,

1114
00:40:20,084 --> 00:40:23,087
-because Young-ok says that looks better.
-I should've made that.

1115
00:40:24,121 --> 00:40:26,457
-What's the tripe like?
-It's also delicious.

1116
00:40:26,524 --> 00:40:27,892
It looks like a Chinese dish.

1117
00:40:27,958 --> 00:40:31,529
I never had a chance
to eat something like this…

1118
00:40:31,595 --> 00:40:33,864
Well, of course not.
Where else am I going to find this?

1119
00:40:33,931 --> 00:40:35,199
It's so different.

1120
00:40:35,266 --> 00:40:36,367
You seem a bit sweaty.

1121
00:40:36,434 --> 00:40:37,968
Yes, I'm getting sweaty.

1122
00:40:38,035 --> 00:40:39,837
-That's the main dish.
-It's so…

1123
00:40:39,904 --> 00:40:41,105
It's so different.

1124
00:40:42,039 --> 00:40:43,507
She takes another bite,

1125
00:40:43,574 --> 00:40:44,408
MMM

1126
00:40:45,810 --> 00:40:46,977
MMM

1127
00:40:47,845 --> 00:40:50,014
Wait, this is an emergency.

1128
00:40:50,080 --> 00:40:51,682
-My gosh.
-I'm getting a headache.

1129
00:40:51,749 --> 00:40:53,551
The process didn't look promising.

1130
00:40:53,617 --> 00:40:54,752
-And the dessert.
-It's so crazy.

1131
00:40:54,819 --> 00:40:56,120
How does he do this?

1132
00:40:56,187 --> 00:40:58,689
-It's a bit…
-I keep hearing the buzzing sound.

1133
00:40:58,756 --> 00:41:00,424
-I can hear the buzz.
-Mmm.

1134
00:41:00,491 --> 00:41:02,293
-Let me try this one too.
-Sure.

1135
00:41:02,359 --> 00:41:05,262
-I'm curious.
-First, cut it with a knife.

1136
00:41:06,597 --> 00:41:07,531
Wow.

1137
00:41:07,598 --> 00:41:09,099
You can cut it.

1138
00:41:09,166 --> 00:41:10,901
It's like a dessert
at a fine dining restaurant.

1139
00:41:10,968 --> 00:41:12,603
-Enough…
-He's never made anything nice.

1140
00:41:12,670 --> 00:41:15,139
-Enough is enough.
-Yes, the dessert.

1141
00:41:15,206 --> 00:41:17,374
What in the world did you make?

1142
00:41:17,441 --> 00:41:18,709
What's that like?

1143
00:41:19,276 --> 00:41:22,513
She's worried it may be too sweet
because he added too much sugar.

1144
00:41:22,580 --> 00:41:24,148
-Hmm?
-What?

1145
00:41:24,215 --> 00:41:25,549
-Wait.
-It's so good.

1146
00:41:27,117 --> 00:41:30,020
WHY DOES THIS ALWAYS HAPPEN
TO NAM-NO?

1147
00:41:30,387 --> 00:41:31,422
THERE IT IS, KIM POONG MAGIC

1148
00:41:31,489 --> 00:41:32,990
-Seriously?
-It's so good.

1149
00:41:34,258 --> 00:41:35,459
I MEAN IT!

1150
00:41:35,526 --> 00:41:37,094
This sounds like big trouble.

1151
00:41:37,161 --> 00:41:40,464
-It's like <i>yugwa.</i>
<i>-Yugwa.</i>

1152
00:41:40,531 --> 00:41:42,600
-How did you do this?
-Is it too sweet?

1153
00:41:42,666 --> 00:41:44,835
-He has great ideas.
-Wow.

1154
00:41:44,902 --> 00:41:47,638
So, which one is the main dish?

1155
00:41:47,705 --> 00:41:49,340
Whichever one she likes better.

1156
00:41:49,607 --> 00:41:50,474
UNBELIEVABLE

1157
00:41:50,541 --> 00:41:51,542
-The dessert.
-Come on!

1158
00:41:51,609 --> 00:41:53,711
That depends on the fridge owner.

1159
00:41:53,777 --> 00:41:56,046
It was so delicious.

1160
00:41:56,113 --> 00:41:58,315
-I can't tell who'll win.
-It's hard to guess.

1161
00:41:58,382 --> 00:41:59,817
You're always like this.

1162
00:41:59,884 --> 00:42:01,785
What do you mean? Don't say that.

1163
00:42:01,852 --> 00:42:03,821
-You don't know yet.
-We don't know.

1164
00:42:03,888 --> 00:42:06,557
Please try Chef Nam-no's dish first.

1165
00:42:06,624 --> 00:42:07,758
All right.

1166
00:42:07,992 --> 00:42:09,226
SNIFF

1167
00:42:09,293 --> 00:42:12,930
-Hong Kong-style fried noodles.
-The eggs are so soft.

1168
00:42:12,997 --> 00:42:14,498
There's pork too.

1169
00:42:15,366 --> 00:42:16,200
I can binge on this.

1170
00:42:16,267 --> 00:42:18,435
-It tastes like Hong Kong.
-It does.

1171
00:42:18,502 --> 00:42:20,771
-The egg is so soft.
-People will binge-eat this.

1172
00:42:20,838 --> 00:42:22,840
Not a lot of people would hate this.

1173
00:42:22,907 --> 00:42:25,075
-It's good.
-It is.

1174
00:42:25,142 --> 00:42:26,777
It's not seasoned too strongly either.

1175
00:42:26,844 --> 00:42:28,612
-It's not as strong as I thought.
-No.

1176
00:42:29,380 --> 00:42:31,015
In Chinese cuisine,

1177
00:42:31,081 --> 00:42:35,119
there are many braised dishes made with
soy sauce, glass noodles, and fritters.

1178
00:42:35,185 --> 00:42:37,254
But today, Chef Nam-no reinterpreted that

1179
00:42:37,321 --> 00:42:39,056
into this friendly noodle dish,

1180
00:42:39,123 --> 00:42:41,458
and I think it's better
than the braised dishes I've had.

1181
00:42:42,626 --> 00:42:45,629
I see. Young-ok continues to eat more.

1182
00:42:45,696 --> 00:42:47,131
Don't you love the egg?

1183
00:42:47,197 --> 00:42:49,600
It's so good, but it's too late at night

1184
00:42:49,667 --> 00:42:51,201
to eat this much.

1185
00:42:51,268 --> 00:42:54,338
She's keeping herself under control,
not to eat too much this late.

1186
00:42:54,405 --> 00:42:55,773
-It's so good.
-All right.

1187
00:42:55,839 --> 00:42:58,809
-Next, Webtoon Artist Poong's dish.
-I've been so curious.

1188
00:42:58,876 --> 00:43:00,778
It's Poong's dish.

1189
00:43:00,844 --> 00:43:02,546
It smells like <i>kimchi-jjigae.</i>

1190
00:43:02,613 --> 00:43:03,547
What is this?

1191
00:43:07,217 --> 00:43:08,052
It's like <i>gopchang-jeongol</i>.

1192
00:43:09,687 --> 00:43:10,821
It's spicy.

1193
00:43:10,888 --> 00:43:13,157
It's different from the previous one.

1194
00:43:18,562 --> 00:43:19,830
It's good.

1195
00:43:19,897 --> 00:43:21,532
The tripe in here is so good.

1196
00:43:21,599 --> 00:43:23,267
It's quite peculiar.

1197
00:43:23,334 --> 00:43:25,569
-What is this?
-The noodles are perfect.

1198
00:43:25,636 --> 00:43:27,271
KIM POONG WORKING HIS MAGIC

1199
00:43:27,338 --> 00:43:28,539
Nice try, Nam-no.

1200
00:43:30,641 --> 00:43:32,409
-It's so good.
-It's good with kimchi.

1201
00:43:32,476 --> 00:43:34,111
-Wow.
-It's good.

1202
00:43:34,178 --> 00:43:36,046
What did you think, Sam?

1203
00:43:36,113 --> 00:43:39,316
When I had Chef Nam-no's dish,

1204
00:43:39,383 --> 00:43:41,819
I was sure that he'd win.

1205
00:43:41,885 --> 00:43:44,922
-But my mind changed after trying this.
-Didn't it?

1206
00:43:44,989 --> 00:43:45,823
This is good.

1207
00:43:45,889 --> 00:43:49,627
Poong, why do you always do so well
against Nam-no? It's so weird.

1208
00:43:49,693 --> 00:43:53,063
This is the first time Sam finished
something Poong has made.

1209
00:43:53,130 --> 00:43:55,799
-It's the first time. He finished it.
-Everything.

1210
00:43:55,866 --> 00:44:00,204
I like how the ground meat
adds a nice texture until the last moment.

1211
00:44:00,270 --> 00:44:03,140
When he added sliced beef briskets,

1212
00:44:03,207 --> 00:44:06,410
<i>it was a wonderful decision</i>
<i>to grind it first.</i>

1213
00:44:06,844 --> 00:44:08,178
POONG THE PROFESSIONAL(?)

1214
00:44:08,245 --> 00:44:09,480
And the dessert.

1215
00:44:09,546 --> 00:44:11,348
SHE WORKS ON THE DESSERT TOO

1216
00:44:11,415 --> 00:44:13,117
You said you couldn't eat too much.

1217
00:44:13,584 --> 00:44:14,752
OH MY MY…

1218
00:44:14,818 --> 00:44:17,187
-Is it not too sweet?
-No, it's not.

1219
00:44:17,254 --> 00:44:19,857
I didn't expect this
from the amount of sugar he used.

1220
00:44:19,923 --> 00:44:22,526
-It's not too sweet.
-It's not?

1221
00:44:22,593 --> 00:44:23,694
I dread giving him this,

1222
00:44:23,761 --> 00:44:25,729
but back when I was in Hong Kong,

1223
00:44:25,796 --> 00:44:27,431
there was a hot and sour noodles place

1224
00:44:27,498 --> 00:44:29,033
where I always ordered from after work,

1225
00:44:29,099 --> 00:44:32,236
and it tastes way too similar
to that delicious restaurant.

1226
00:44:32,836 --> 00:44:33,704
It's that good?

1227
00:44:33,771 --> 00:44:35,172
He should open a restaurant.

1228
00:44:35,239 --> 00:44:36,440
Honestly speaking,

1229
00:44:36,507 --> 00:44:38,375
I'm always doing my best
to hold on to my sanity

1230
00:44:38,976 --> 00:44:39,877
not to be moved

1231
00:44:40,444 --> 00:44:42,012
by any dish that man makes.

1232
00:44:43,614 --> 00:44:45,382
I just found myself

1233
00:44:45,449 --> 00:44:47,885
indulging and devouring his dish right now

1234
00:44:47,951 --> 00:44:49,453
and became very upset.

1235
00:44:49,687 --> 00:44:51,588
ME, A FEW MINUTES AGO…

1236
00:44:51,855 --> 00:44:52,756
Wow.

1237
00:44:53,223 --> 00:44:54,058
SLURP

1238
00:44:54,792 --> 00:44:55,826
SLURP

1239
00:44:56,727 --> 00:44:57,561
SLURP

1240
00:44:58,462 --> 00:45:00,197
AND EVEN THE SOUP…

1241
00:45:00,964 --> 00:45:02,900
THAT WAS A NICE MEAL

1242
00:45:02,966 --> 00:45:04,334
It feels like

1243
00:45:04,401 --> 00:45:07,538
he gets blindly lucky
when he makes these dishes,

1244
00:45:07,604 --> 00:45:10,340
but why does it turn out so deliciously?

1245
00:45:10,941 --> 00:45:12,443
You must be torn.

1246
00:45:12,509 --> 00:45:14,244
I'm so torn right now.

1247
00:45:14,311 --> 00:45:17,614
One of them was perfect for my palate,

1248
00:45:17,681 --> 00:45:20,584
but the other was so new and fun.

1249
00:45:20,651 --> 00:45:22,753
That's my situation right now,
and I'm quite torn.

1250
00:45:22,820 --> 00:45:24,755
All right, then.

1251
00:45:24,822 --> 00:45:27,725
-It's a tough decision.
-Please make your choice.

1252
00:45:27,791 --> 00:45:28,759
You have to do this.

1253
00:45:28,826 --> 00:45:32,563
These two are fighting each other again
in the 2026 season.

1254
00:45:32,629 --> 00:45:34,431
<i>Press one for Yoon Nam-no</i>

1255
00:45:34,498 --> 00:45:36,500
<i>and two for Kim Poong.</i>

1256
00:45:36,567 --> 00:45:39,570
Please make your decision
and press the button!

1257
00:45:40,504 --> 00:45:42,873
-Both dishes were so good.
-I see.

1258
00:45:42,940 --> 00:45:44,975
-Pick just one person.
-Just one.

1259
00:45:45,042 --> 00:45:46,443
She must have a good reason.

1260
00:45:46,510 --> 00:45:48,212
-Please!
-Did you push it?

1261
00:45:48,278 --> 00:45:50,347
-I did.
-She did.

1262
00:45:51,715 --> 00:45:52,549
I'm curious.

1263
00:45:52,616 --> 00:45:54,651
Which one did you like better?

1264
00:45:54,718 --> 00:45:57,454
You can't ask me that now.

1265
00:45:57,521 --> 00:45:59,923
-All right. I put you on the spot.
-Both were good.

1266
00:45:59,990 --> 00:46:01,291
Both were good.

1267
00:46:01,358 --> 00:46:03,260
Let us find out the result.

1268
00:46:03,327 --> 00:46:04,695
Show us!

1269
00:46:04,762 --> 00:46:06,697
This is Jun-myun's decision.

1270
00:46:06,764 --> 00:46:09,032
Can You Win Against <i>Japchae?</i>

1271
00:46:09,099 --> 00:46:11,635
Poong had been a strong contender
when up against Nam-no,

1272
00:46:11,702 --> 00:46:15,172
so will he keep it going this year
and continue to win against him?

1273
00:46:15,239 --> 00:46:18,242
-Or will Nam-no change this year?
-No way.

1274
00:46:18,308 --> 00:46:21,678
Can he win against Poong?

1275
00:46:21,745 --> 00:46:25,048
Which noodle dish did Jun-myun prefer?

1276
00:46:25,115 --> 00:46:26,250
What's the result?

1277
00:46:29,620 --> 00:46:31,388
Jun-myun's choice!

1278
00:46:31,455 --> 00:46:33,323
KIM POONG WINS

1279
00:46:34,758 --> 00:46:37,027
KIM POONG'S
GLASS NOODLE QUEEN WINS

1280
00:46:37,694 --> 00:46:38,529
5 CONSECUTIVE LOSSES

1281
00:46:38,595 --> 00:46:40,697
-Kim Poong wins!
-You lost!

1282
00:46:40,764 --> 00:46:42,266
Take this bop.

1283
00:46:44,568 --> 00:46:46,303
-What is this?
-Really?

1284
00:46:46,370 --> 00:46:47,771
Five consecutive losses.

1285
00:46:48,739 --> 00:46:50,274
-It's an emergency.
-It was also good,

1286
00:46:50,340 --> 00:46:53,277
-but it was a minute difference.
-It's not like Nam-no is a bad cook.

1287
00:46:53,343 --> 00:46:55,245
I would pay for this
if he opened a restaurant.

1288
00:46:55,312 --> 00:46:56,413
I'm feeling pain right now.

1289
00:46:56,480 --> 00:46:58,115
This was such a new dish,

1290
00:46:58,182 --> 00:47:00,918
-and it had a chance against <i>japchae.</i>
-It does.

1291
00:47:00,984 --> 00:47:03,220
-That was the theme…
-It doesn't even look like <i>japchae.</i>

1292
00:47:03,287 --> 00:47:05,689
…so I had to choose him.

1293
00:47:07,090 --> 00:47:09,626
This means he won five times in a row

1294
00:47:09,693 --> 00:47:11,328
just against Nam-no.

1295
00:47:11,395 --> 00:47:14,731
I'm starting to wonder
if it's okay for him to cook so well.

1296
00:47:14,798 --> 00:47:16,400
Do you see why he won?

1297
00:47:16,466 --> 00:47:17,434
Sure.

1298
00:47:17,501 --> 00:47:18,335
OH, MY

1299
00:47:20,237 --> 00:47:23,440
-No, I was on Nam-no's side.
-I see.

1300
00:47:23,507 --> 00:47:25,175
Right?

1301
00:47:25,242 --> 00:47:27,911
I took many risks while making this today,

1302
00:47:27,978 --> 00:47:29,112
so I thought

1303
00:47:29,179 --> 00:47:31,882
I had given him enough chances.

1304
00:47:31,949 --> 00:47:33,884
What does that make of me?

1305
00:47:33,951 --> 00:47:35,853
I thought it was too experimental.

1306
00:47:35,919 --> 00:47:38,021
What do you call it? A fluke?

1307
00:47:38,088 --> 00:47:40,023
-Good luck.
-A fluke.

1308
00:47:40,090 --> 00:47:41,925
I think it was a fluke

1309
00:47:41,992 --> 00:47:44,027
-that I won this one.
-I see.

1310
00:47:44,094 --> 00:47:45,229
Mom…

1311
00:47:46,230 --> 00:47:49,800
This means Poong now has
the same number of stars as Hyun-suk.

1312
00:47:49,867 --> 00:47:51,535
HYUN-SUK AND POONG BOTH WON ONCE

1313
00:47:51,602 --> 00:47:53,136
That's huge.

1314
00:47:53,203 --> 00:47:56,506
-You never know how this show will go.
-Please put a star on Poong!

1315
00:47:57,007 --> 00:48:00,143
Poong has won once again,
as we begin the new year.

1316
00:48:00,210 --> 00:48:02,179
-Congratulations.
-Thank you.

1317
00:48:02,246 --> 00:48:04,314
It's Poong's first star of the year!

1318
00:48:04,381 --> 00:48:06,183
-Congratulations!
-It was so good.

1319
00:48:07,684 --> 00:48:09,753
That is so strange.

1320
00:48:09,820 --> 00:48:11,321
It's so strange.

1321
00:48:11,388 --> 00:48:13,090
You should start a business.

1322
00:48:13,156 --> 00:48:14,958
Start what business? Come on.

1323
00:48:15,759 --> 00:48:20,130
<i>We're about to begin the second cook-off</i>
<i>with Jun-myun's ingredients.</i>

1324
00:48:20,197 --> 00:48:24,368
The hottest man as of this moment,
Chef Son Jong-won,

1325
00:48:24,434 --> 00:48:27,404
versus the man who feels the emptiest
at this moment,

1326
00:48:27,471 --> 00:48:31,775
-Chef Kwon Sung-jun.
-So very empty.

1327
00:48:31,842 --> 00:48:35,779
With Chef Jong-won's recent rise
as the most buzzworthy person,

1328
00:48:35,846 --> 00:48:40,284
Chef Sung-jun slowly became
quite stressed.

1329
00:48:40,350 --> 00:48:41,184
Why is that?

1330
00:48:41,251 --> 00:48:42,653
First of all, in my case,

1331
00:48:42,719 --> 00:48:45,689
even as I seized my victory
on <i>Culinary Class Wars,</i>

1332
00:48:45,756 --> 00:48:47,457
I didn't make
the top ten buzzworthy people.

1333
00:48:48,125 --> 00:48:51,395
Chef Edward Lee was
the most buzzworthy back then.

1334
00:48:51,461 --> 00:48:53,597
-He's so frank.
-Chef Edward stole the thunder.

1335
00:48:53,664 --> 00:48:56,099
-But he should've been buzzworthy.
-Yes.

1336
00:48:56,166 --> 00:48:58,101
He's slowly being forgotten.

1337
00:48:58,168 --> 00:48:59,603
What's this about?

1338
00:48:59,670 --> 00:49:00,938
Did you spend last night

1339
00:49:01,004 --> 00:49:04,541
just looking at your phone
from dusk to dawn?

1340
00:49:04,608 --> 00:49:05,676
I know what that's about.

1341
00:49:05,742 --> 00:49:07,644
-Why?
-What's going on?

1342
00:49:07,711 --> 00:49:10,180
He's the target of my jealousy,

1343
00:49:10,247 --> 00:49:12,416
and there was only one thing
I was winning at,

1344
00:49:12,482 --> 00:49:14,217
the number of followers on social media.

1345
00:49:14,284 --> 00:49:16,620
-Your followers.
-I originally had the most followers

1346
00:49:16,687 --> 00:49:18,555
among Korean chefs…

1347
00:49:18,622 --> 00:49:20,624
-And he knows this?
-…but he began to catch up.

1348
00:49:20,691 --> 00:49:23,894
But today, on this day, at 1:30 a.m.,

1349
00:49:23,961 --> 00:49:25,562
he recorded 411,000 followers…

1350
00:49:25,629 --> 00:49:28,899
-You were still awake?
-…surpassed my number,

1351
00:49:28,966 --> 00:49:31,401
-and now has the most followers.
-Does he?

1352
00:49:31,468 --> 00:49:32,703
How unfortunate.

1353
00:49:32,769 --> 00:49:35,973
-That was the one number he was ahead in.
-I even lost that.

1354
00:49:36,039 --> 00:49:38,675
He doesn't even care,
but Sung-jun is so caught up on it.

1355
00:49:38,742 --> 00:49:41,144
He was looking at it at 1:30 a.m.

1356
00:49:41,211 --> 00:49:43,814
-How heartbreaking.
-He was upset, wasn't he?

1357
00:49:43,880 --> 00:49:45,449
You beat him today at 1:30 a.m.

1358
00:49:45,515 --> 00:49:47,117
-I'd like to let you know.
-Well…

1359
00:49:47,184 --> 00:49:48,452
Sure.

1360
00:49:48,518 --> 00:49:49,753
DOESN'T GET SUNG-JUN

1361
00:49:49,820 --> 00:49:51,655
-Thanks.
-It doesn't seem important to him.

1362
00:49:51,722 --> 00:49:52,689
Please be happy.

1363
00:49:52,990 --> 00:49:54,691
AS HAPPY AS HE CAN BE

1364
00:49:54,925 --> 00:49:56,994
WOO-HOO, SO HAPPY

1365
00:49:57,060 --> 00:49:59,463
I've been doing just about everything

1366
00:49:59,529 --> 00:50:01,264
to maintain my number of followers,

1367
00:50:02,265 --> 00:50:03,734
<i>such as trolling people</i>

1368
00:50:03,800 --> 00:50:05,502
<i>and starring on YouTube channels.</i>

1369
00:50:05,569 --> 00:50:08,572
But whenever Chef Jong-won
uploads a selfie,

1370
00:50:08,638 --> 00:50:10,273
I see him gain 100,000 followers per post.

1371
00:50:10,340 --> 00:50:11,708
100,000-FOLLOWER GROWTH SPURTS

1372
00:50:11,775 --> 00:50:13,543
-Why do you care? You're a chef.
-I feel bad.

1373
00:50:13,610 --> 00:50:15,145
-It was heartbreaking.
-I've had enough.

1374
00:50:15,212 --> 00:50:17,047
I see. That can happen.

1375
00:50:17,114 --> 00:50:19,216
I don't think there's anyone

1376
00:50:19,282 --> 00:50:23,353
who ranks the number of followers
we Korean chefs have.

1377
00:50:23,520 --> 00:50:25,188
CONGRATS,
YOU'RE THE 1ST TO DO THAT

1378
00:50:25,255 --> 00:50:27,057
-I didn't even know you could.
-The number of followers.

1379
00:50:27,424 --> 00:50:29,659
THE BEST ANALYST IN KOREA

1380
00:50:29,726 --> 00:50:31,762
Do you know
how many followers Chef Hyun-suk has?

1381
00:50:31,828 --> 00:50:33,397
I believe he has

1382
00:50:33,463 --> 00:50:35,632
-about 280,000 followers.
-He keeps track of everyone.

1383
00:50:35,699 --> 00:50:37,467
You're diligently checking everyone?

1384
00:50:37,534 --> 00:50:39,302
Chef Sam has
about 270,000 followers as well.

1385
00:50:39,870 --> 00:50:41,104
291,000 FOLLOWERS

1386
00:50:41,171 --> 00:50:44,508
Under them are Poong and Nam-no,
with mid-200,000 followers.

1387
00:50:44,574 --> 00:50:45,575
He calls it "under."

1388
00:50:45,642 --> 00:50:48,078
Under them are Eun-yeong and Ho-young,

1389
00:50:48,145 --> 00:50:51,048
about the same, around 100,000 followers.

1390
00:50:51,114 --> 00:50:52,716
The last place.

1391
00:50:52,783 --> 00:50:54,217
That's why he looks down on me.

1392
00:50:54,284 --> 00:50:56,053
Yes, he does. It shows in his eyes.

1393
00:50:56,119 --> 00:50:57,821
You're really scary.

1394
00:50:57,888 --> 00:50:59,122
Are all Gen Z kids like him these days?

1395
00:50:59,189 --> 00:51:01,725
I get angry whenever he does that.

1396
00:51:01,792 --> 00:51:03,360
Why would you be mad?

1397
00:51:03,427 --> 00:51:06,029
-He's not even on par with Jong-won.
-Though he should be?

1398
00:51:06,096 --> 00:51:07,030
LOL

1399
00:51:07,097 --> 00:51:08,532
No one is siding with Sung-jun.

1400
00:51:08,598 --> 00:51:09,866
-Gosh.
-That's awful.

1401
00:51:09,933 --> 00:51:11,334
We're rooting for you, Sung-jun.

1402
00:51:11,401 --> 00:51:13,937
Chef Sung-jun has short limbs,

1403
00:51:14,004 --> 00:51:15,205
but he's a handsome man.

1404
00:51:15,539 --> 00:51:17,774
SHORT LIMBS

1405
00:51:17,841 --> 00:51:21,278
It's not that his limbs are short.
He just has high body fat.

1406
00:51:21,344 --> 00:51:23,346
HANDSOME WITH SHORT LIMBS
AS APPROVED BY EUN-YEONG

1407
00:51:23,413 --> 00:51:25,215
You all seem to have a lot of fun.

1408
00:51:25,582 --> 00:51:27,317
THAT'S LIFE HERE ON THE SHOW
THESE DAYS

1409
00:51:27,384 --> 00:51:29,352
It's a great thing.

1410
00:51:29,920 --> 00:51:30,787
Jealousy and envy?

1411
00:51:30,854 --> 00:51:32,589
He's jealous of Jong-won

1412
00:51:32,656 --> 00:51:35,392
and wants to copy him even more, right?

1413
00:51:35,459 --> 00:51:37,527
-But I'm like that too.
-Yes, of course!

1414
00:51:37,594 --> 00:51:40,263
When I feel like
someone is doing better than I am,

1415
00:51:40,330 --> 00:51:41,665
even I get jealous.

1416
00:51:41,731 --> 00:51:44,267
-He can't grow at that age without that.
-You're right.

1417
00:51:44,334 --> 00:51:46,203
That's true. It's a healthy emotion.

1418
00:51:46,269 --> 00:51:48,905
-It's good, and that was honest of you.
-It means you have energy.

1419
00:51:48,972 --> 00:51:50,907
-It's like that.
-She's great.

1420
00:51:50,974 --> 00:51:53,677
The order for this round
is a fine dining experience.

1421
00:51:53,743 --> 00:51:56,780
Chef Jong-won has never lost,
not even once,

1422
00:51:56,847 --> 00:51:59,049
whenever he had to create
fine dining dishes.

1423
00:51:59,116 --> 00:52:02,219
<i>It looks like he chose the wrong order.</i>

1424
00:52:02,285 --> 00:52:04,054
Actually, I've been to his restaurant

1425
00:52:04,121 --> 00:52:05,522
-and finished analyzing.
-You did?

1426
00:52:05,589 --> 00:52:07,157
FINISHED ANALYZING
HIS RESTAURANT

1427
00:52:07,224 --> 00:52:10,227
But he's never been to my restaurant,

1428
00:52:10,293 --> 00:52:12,028
and it doesn't seem like he wants to come.

1429
00:52:13,096 --> 00:52:15,298
-I probably have the upper hand.
-That was blunt.

1430
00:52:15,365 --> 00:52:17,267
Jong-won doesn't care.
Why are you hung up on him?

1431
00:52:17,334 --> 00:52:19,269
Why are you boxing shadows?

1432
00:52:19,336 --> 00:52:21,004
He's been to his restaurant too.

1433
00:52:21,838 --> 00:52:23,907
CHEF JONG-WON'S INGREDIENTS:
SMOKED CHICKEN, BREAD, APPLE, PEACH JAM

1434
00:52:23,974 --> 00:52:26,009
CHESTNUT HONEY, SCALLION, MAYO,
CREAM CHEESE, MUSTARD, AND MORE

1435
00:52:26,076 --> 00:52:28,345
Chef Jong-won, what are you making?

1436
00:52:28,411 --> 00:52:30,247
The name of my dish is

1437
00:52:30,313 --> 00:52:33,717
Les Misérables French-Style Dining.

1438
00:52:33,783 --> 00:52:38,421
-Les Misérables French-Style Dining.
-Les Misérables French-Style Dining.

1439
00:52:38,488 --> 00:52:40,857
Why do you
always name your dishes so long?

1440
00:52:40,924 --> 00:52:44,361
Eat Banana Crêpe, Yong-bok,
and Get Lucky, Lee Know?

1441
00:52:44,427 --> 00:52:48,398
Your Son's Too Hot, Sorry Mom's Lunch Box.

1442
00:52:48,965 --> 00:52:50,367
I have too much to say.

1443
00:52:50,634 --> 00:52:51,668
A BIG LAUGH

1444
00:52:51,735 --> 00:52:54,704
Long titles are in trend right now.

1445
00:52:55,272 --> 00:52:57,007
The crew member who writes captions says
it's too hard.

1446
00:52:57,073 --> 00:52:59,543
-It is rather long.
-Our crew asked me to relay that.

1447
00:52:59,609 --> 00:53:01,111
We already lost two members, right?

1448
00:53:01,178 --> 00:53:03,013
Yes, they couldn't do it anymore.

1449
00:53:03,079 --> 00:53:06,283
It's called
Les Misérables French-Style Dining.

1450
00:53:06,349 --> 00:53:09,319
-It was one of the musicals you were in.
-Yes.

1451
00:53:09,386 --> 00:53:11,721
I'm making a dish called rillettes.

1452
00:53:11,788 --> 00:53:14,724
It's nothing complicated.
It's a kind of spread made with meat

1453
00:53:14,791 --> 00:53:16,893
usually eaten with bread.

1454
00:53:16,960 --> 00:53:19,796
It may seem like a basic French dish,

1455
00:53:19,863 --> 00:53:21,531
but I'll reinterpret it

1456
00:53:21,598 --> 00:53:24,734
into a fine dining experience
so that it feels much more familiar.

1457
00:53:25,001 --> 00:53:26,036
EAGER

1458
00:53:26,870 --> 00:53:28,939
CHEF SUNG-JUN'S INGREDIENTS:
PORK BELLY, PREPPED TRIPE, DRIED POLLACK

1459
00:53:29,005 --> 00:53:31,041
PERILLA OIL, SESAME OIL, OYSTER SAUCE,
CHIVE, NAPA CABBAGE, RADISH, AND MORE

1460
00:53:31,107 --> 00:53:33,143
The name of my dish is

1461
00:53:33,210 --> 00:53:34,377
Son Stealer.

1462
00:53:34,444 --> 00:53:36,580
-Son Stealer.
-Son Stealer.

1463
00:53:36,646 --> 00:53:38,448
Son Stealer. What does that mean?

1464
00:53:38,515 --> 00:53:42,252
It means I will steal
Chef Jong-won's popularity and followers.

1465
00:53:42,819 --> 00:53:46,489
-You'll steal them all?
-It means that I'll steal them quickly.

1466
00:53:46,556 --> 00:53:48,058
Well, it was a joke,

1467
00:53:48,124 --> 00:53:50,427
but as a chef
who also makes fine dining dishes,

1468
00:53:50,493 --> 00:53:53,096
I prepared for this round
with all seriousness.

1469
00:53:53,163 --> 00:53:55,599
So today, I'll make <i>dwaeji-gukbap</i>,
pork and rice soup.

1470
00:53:55,665 --> 00:53:58,001
You'll turn <i>dwaeji-gukbap</i>
into a fine dining experience?

1471
00:53:58,068 --> 00:54:00,503
I'll reinterpret it my way

1472
00:54:00,570 --> 00:54:02,372
and start the dish as Korean food

1473
00:54:02,439 --> 00:54:07,143
but finish the experience
with a flavor of Italy.

1474
00:54:07,210 --> 00:54:11,214
I also prepared
a different kind of presentation.

1475
00:54:11,481 --> 00:54:14,451
EXCITED

1476
00:54:14,517 --> 00:54:17,387
-You must boil the soup for a long time.
-That is so.

1477
00:54:17,954 --> 00:54:22,158
Time to begin "It'd Be Nice If Someone
Gave Me the Fine Dining Experience."

1478
00:54:22,225 --> 00:54:24,928
The man who attracts a crowd
without doing anything,

1479
00:54:24,995 --> 00:54:27,230
the most buzzworthy person,
Chef Son Jong-won,

1480
00:54:27,297 --> 00:54:30,734
versus the man who's afraid people
will leave if he doesn't do anything,

1481
00:54:30,800 --> 00:54:34,971
the most attention-seeking person,
Chef Kwon Sung-jun.

1482
00:54:35,038 --> 00:54:37,574
Who'll present the best
fine dining experience on this show?

1483
00:54:37,641 --> 00:54:40,677
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1484
00:54:41,711 --> 00:54:43,146
CHEERING

1485
00:54:43,546 --> 00:54:44,547
CALM, BUSY

1486
00:54:44,881 --> 00:54:46,583
THE MOST FOLLOWERS
VS. THE FORMER CHAMPION

1487
00:54:46,650 --> 00:54:49,519
This will be another interesting round.

1488
00:54:49,586 --> 00:54:53,156
Naturally, he picks up bread
for Les Misérables, like Jean Valjean.

1489
00:54:53,223 --> 00:54:55,492
Jean Valjean and Les Misérables French.

1490
00:54:56,493 --> 00:54:58,194
-"Style."
-Les Misérables French.

1491
00:54:58,261 --> 00:54:59,929
-Dining.
-"Style" sounds like my name.

1492
00:54:59,996 --> 00:55:02,098
MY GOSH

1493
00:55:03,466 --> 00:55:04,934
1. CUT OFF THE EDGES
AND ROLL THE BREAD FLAT

1494
00:55:05,001 --> 00:55:06,536
Chef Jong-won is working with bread.

1495
00:55:06,603 --> 00:55:09,873
-Yes.
-He's making crispy shells with bread.

1496
00:55:09,939 --> 00:55:12,509
I didn't know you could do that
with regular plain bread.

1497
00:55:13,443 --> 00:55:15,645
-Is that pork?
-Yes, it's pork.

1498
00:55:15,712 --> 00:55:16,980
It's pork belly.

1499
00:55:17,047 --> 00:55:18,415
Sung-jun uses pork.

1500
00:55:18,481 --> 00:55:19,316
Pork belly soup.

1501
00:55:19,382 --> 00:55:22,352
You said you'd make the pork soup first.

1502
00:55:22,419 --> 00:55:24,454
-Isn't the meat too thick?
-Sesame oil?

1503
00:55:24,521 --> 00:55:26,790
-He's trying to make a broth.
-It's for the broth?

1504
00:55:26,856 --> 00:55:27,857
DROPPING PREPPED TRIPE!

1505
00:55:27,924 --> 00:55:29,092
He's using tripe as well.

1506
00:55:29,159 --> 00:55:31,561
-What's that?
-It's dried pollack.

1507
00:55:31,628 --> 00:55:33,396
He doesn't spare the ingredients.

1508
00:55:33,463 --> 00:55:35,298
Doesn't he have to boil that
for <i>dwaeji-gukbap?</i>

1509
00:55:35,365 --> 00:55:37,567
He's going to change the dish

1510
00:55:37,634 --> 00:55:39,869
into something you'll get
at a classy restaurant.

1511
00:55:39,936 --> 00:55:41,004
He'll add a twist.

1512
00:55:41,071 --> 00:55:43,540
-Can he do that?
-Les Misérables French.

1513
00:55:43,606 --> 00:55:46,710
Sung-jun looks determined today.

1514
00:55:46,776 --> 00:55:48,311
-He's serious.
-He is.

1515
00:55:48,378 --> 00:55:51,147
-He's yet to win a star this season.
-Right.

1516
00:55:51,214 --> 00:55:53,950
It looks like he's making <i>dwaeji-gukbap.</i>

1517
00:55:54,984 --> 00:55:56,052
GLOVE ON

1518
00:55:56,720 --> 00:56:00,357
At a fine dining restaurant,
not only is the food delicious and deep,

1519
00:56:00,423 --> 00:56:03,493
but the presentation is also beautiful.

1520
00:56:03,560 --> 00:56:04,627
They work hard on that.

1521
00:56:04,694 --> 00:56:06,896
I see. The presentation.

1522
00:56:06,963 --> 00:56:09,232
Chef Jong-won is creating a shape.

1523
00:56:09,299 --> 00:56:10,133
The mold.

1524
00:56:10,200 --> 00:56:12,035
And he… Is that dessert?

1525
00:56:12,102 --> 00:56:16,106
It's not, but he's making crispy shells
to fill the spread with.

1526
00:56:17,774 --> 00:56:19,175
He's making tart shells.

1527
00:56:19,242 --> 00:56:22,078
-He's pushing down on the bread.
-He is.

1528
00:56:22,145 --> 00:56:23,480
Tart shells.

1529
00:56:24,114 --> 00:56:26,082
He already used
almost three minutes doing that.

1530
00:56:26,583 --> 00:56:30,153
2. PUT PLAIN BREAD IN A TART MOLD
AND BAKE IN THE OVEN

1531
00:56:32,088 --> 00:56:33,256
PORK BELLY

1532
00:56:34,557 --> 00:56:36,292
-What's that? Gochujang?
-What is that?

1533
00:56:36,359 --> 00:56:37,660
Salted hairtail.

1534
00:56:37,727 --> 00:56:40,230
He's grinding pork belly
with salted hairtail.

1535
00:56:40,463 --> 00:56:41,698
I LOVE SALTED HAIRTAIL

1536
00:56:41,765 --> 00:56:42,999
-Salted hairtail.
-It's so good.

1537
00:56:43,066 --> 00:56:44,968
-Oyster sauce.
-He used

1538
00:56:45,034 --> 00:56:46,269
both oyster sauce and hairtail.

1539
00:56:46,336 --> 00:56:48,638
It's impossible to make that taste bad.

1540
00:56:48,705 --> 00:56:50,106
-Yes.
-He doesn't have much time.

1541
00:56:50,874 --> 00:56:53,443
It may seem like
a fight against your opponent,

1542
00:56:53,510 --> 00:56:55,845
but you're also fighting yourself.

1543
00:56:55,912 --> 00:56:58,548
Sung-jun is also fighting
for the number of followers.

1544
00:57:00,250 --> 00:57:03,820
He might rake in many followers
if he wins the round today.

1545
00:57:04,587 --> 00:57:06,923
THE PRINCE OF FOLLOWERS
GETS SCALLIONS READY

1546
00:57:07,357 --> 00:57:08,191
GRABS A KNIFE

1547
00:57:11,895 --> 00:57:13,830
He's cutting the scallion delicately.

1548
00:57:13,897 --> 00:57:16,099
-It's a fine dining skill.
-What's he doing?

1549
00:57:16,166 --> 00:57:17,634
They'll open up like flower blossoms.

1550
00:57:17,934 --> 00:57:18,768
FLOWERS?

1551
00:57:18,835 --> 00:57:20,036
They'll look like flowers.

1552
00:57:20,103 --> 00:57:22,372
-Those?
-Is that the case?

1553
00:57:22,439 --> 00:57:24,140
They'll look like flowers?

1554
00:57:24,207 --> 00:57:26,476
They'll come alive
as soon as they're in cold water.

1555
00:57:26,543 --> 00:57:28,077
-Really?
-Really?

1556
00:57:28,144 --> 00:57:29,479
-That's fascinating.
-You can do that?

1557
00:57:29,546 --> 00:57:31,147
Will he use those chopped pieces?

1558
00:57:31,214 --> 00:57:34,117
They'll turn into V-shapes.

1559
00:57:34,184 --> 00:57:35,985
-V-shapes?
-V-shapes.

1560
00:57:36,252 --> 00:57:37,954
SUNG-JUN FIGHTS HIM WITH CHIVES

1561
00:57:38,021 --> 00:57:39,255
Is he using hot water

1562
00:57:39,322 --> 00:57:41,057
-to cook them slightly?
-Yes.

1563
00:57:41,124 --> 00:57:42,826
He's blanching the chives.

1564
00:57:42,892 --> 00:57:44,127
Isn't it better to dip it for a second?

1565
00:57:44,194 --> 00:57:46,463
He's been doing so well lately

1566
00:57:46,529 --> 00:57:47,964
that he's even trying to teach us chefs.

1567
00:57:48,431 --> 00:57:49,532
WATCH IT

1568
00:57:49,599 --> 00:57:50,934
-Why does he do that?
-He now asks

1569
00:57:51,000 --> 00:57:52,435
the winner of <i>Culinary Class Wars,</i>

1570
00:57:52,502 --> 00:57:54,804
-"Why do you do that?"
-Isn't it the same thing?

1571
00:57:54,871 --> 00:57:57,574
-It's to cut down on time.
-To save time?

1572
00:57:57,974 --> 00:57:59,843
+ OLIVE OIL - 3. BLEND CHIVES
AND OIL TO MAKE CHIVE OIL

1573
00:57:59,909 --> 00:58:00,944
He's blending something.

1574
00:58:01,010 --> 00:58:03,246
-He's making chive oil with oil.
-That's oil.

1575
00:58:03,313 --> 00:58:04,147
Chive oil.

1576
00:58:04,214 --> 00:58:06,649
-He did it.
-It looks good.

1577
00:58:06,716 --> 00:58:08,418
-Look at the color.
-It looks so vibrant.

1578
00:58:08,485 --> 00:58:09,686
It's like chlorophyll.

1579
00:58:09,752 --> 00:58:13,556
Chef Sung-jun is too focused
and can't hear anything.

1580
00:58:13,623 --> 00:58:14,691
Look at that focus.

1581
00:58:14,757 --> 00:58:16,025
That's the fine dining code.

1582
00:58:16,092 --> 00:58:18,695
I see. Sung-jun begins to focus.

1583
00:58:18,761 --> 00:58:23,433
-He's making delicious <i>dwaeji-gukbap.</i>
-How will he do that?

1584
00:58:23,500 --> 00:58:25,668
You can't find that
at a fine dining restaurant.

1585
00:58:25,735 --> 00:58:27,871
I guess he's actually making
<i>dwaeji-gukbap.</i>

1586
00:58:27,937 --> 00:58:29,239
Yes, he actually is.

1587
00:58:29,305 --> 00:58:31,040
He threw in vegetables.

1588
00:58:31,107 --> 00:58:34,611
Chef Jong-won knows presentation
is important for a fine dining experience.

1589
00:58:34,677 --> 00:58:36,179
-The smoked…
-It's a bar snack.

1590
00:58:36,246 --> 00:58:38,248
-Her husband got that…
-A bar snack.

1591
00:58:38,314 --> 00:58:41,718
-…from a convenience store. He's using it.
-He got it while he was drunk.

1592
00:58:42,719 --> 00:58:45,088
SMOKED CHICKEN AND MAYONNAISE

1593
00:58:46,256 --> 00:58:48,224
BOTTLE CAP

1594
00:58:48,291 --> 00:58:51,327
After he squeezes out the mayo,

1595
00:58:51,394 --> 00:58:54,030
he puts the cap back on.

1596
00:58:54,097 --> 00:58:55,131
Gosh.

1597
00:58:55,198 --> 00:58:57,667
-We don't do that.
-Because of the time limit.

1598
00:58:57,734 --> 00:58:59,869
-We usually just throw it aside.
-Yes.

1599
00:58:59,936 --> 00:59:03,273
I don't know who his teacher is,
but he has a wonderful habit.

1600
00:59:03,339 --> 00:59:04,774
Tell me about it.

1601
00:59:04,841 --> 00:59:06,209
3. GRIND
AND MAKE CHICKEN RILLETTES

1602
00:59:06,276 --> 00:59:08,244
He's grinding smoked chicken with mayo.

1603
00:59:08,311 --> 00:59:09,379
-Is he?
-Yes.

1604
00:59:09,445 --> 00:59:12,148
He's grinding smoked chicken with mayo?

1605
00:59:12,215 --> 00:59:15,485
-Chicken, Dijon mustard, and…
-He's adding oil too.

1606
00:59:15,552 --> 00:59:18,621
It usually needs Dijon mustard and fat.

1607
00:59:18,688 --> 00:59:22,058
Once the fat is mixed in,
you use it like a spread for bread.

1608
00:59:22,125 --> 00:59:24,160
It's usually made with pork,

1609
00:59:24,227 --> 00:59:25,895
but he's using chicken instead.

1610
00:59:25,962 --> 00:59:27,497
-I see.
-It's already seasoned too.

1611
00:59:27,564 --> 00:59:30,867
He added mayo instead of fat
and began to mix it in.

1612
00:59:30,934 --> 00:59:33,836
Chef Jong-won is still in France.

1613
00:59:33,903 --> 00:59:34,971
ADD BLACK PEPPER!

1614
00:59:37,907 --> 00:59:38,775
What's that?

1615
00:59:39,509 --> 00:59:41,945
-Dried shiitake?
-Is it dried mushrooms?

1616
00:59:42,011 --> 00:59:43,379
Dried shiitake and kelp.

1617
00:59:43,446 --> 00:59:44,681
-Dried shiitake.
-Dried shiitake and kelp.

1618
00:59:44,747 --> 00:59:45,682
Kelp?

1619
00:59:45,748 --> 00:59:46,950
What's that for?

1620
00:59:47,016 --> 00:59:48,751
The powder will have strong umami.

1621
00:59:48,818 --> 00:59:50,119
Right, I see.

1622
00:59:50,186 --> 00:59:52,822
He made that… I see.
She had shepherd's purse too?

1623
00:59:52,889 --> 00:59:55,258
-No, that's wild chive.
-Wild chive.

1624
00:59:55,725 --> 00:59:58,061
DOES HE HAVE A PLAN TO INCREASE
THE NUMBER OF FOLLOWERS?

1625
00:59:59,996 --> 01:00:02,332
STEALING HIS CHOPPING SKILLS!

1626
01:00:02,899 --> 01:00:06,736
EVERYTHING YOU HAVE
SHOULD'VE BEEN MINE

1627
01:00:07,437 --> 01:00:09,005
Gosh, it's eight minutes already.

1628
01:00:09,072 --> 01:00:12,442
Young-ok just shared
that you have eight minutes left.

1629
01:00:13,142 --> 01:00:14,644
It's an emergency.

1630
01:00:14,711 --> 01:00:16,446
-Emergency?
-An emergency? Why?

1631
01:00:16,512 --> 01:00:17,747
I just need to move faster.

1632
01:00:17,814 --> 01:00:18,781
You have to hurry.

1633
01:00:18,848 --> 01:00:19,849
Hurry up.

1634
01:00:19,916 --> 01:00:22,885
-Hurry up. You can do this.
-Things went well when Poong used kimchi.

1635
01:00:23,753 --> 01:00:25,221
That kimchi is a nice kick.

1636
01:00:25,288 --> 01:00:27,991
-Is he making wraps?
-He's wrapping ground pork inside kimchi.

1637
01:00:28,324 --> 01:00:29,892
OHHHHH

1638
01:00:29,959 --> 01:00:31,160
That has to be good.

1639
01:00:31,227 --> 01:00:32,662
It has to be.

1640
01:00:32,729 --> 01:00:34,130
-It looks so good.
-It has to be.

1641
01:00:34,197 --> 01:00:37,166
-Is this a Korean fine dining experience?
-It is.

1642
01:00:37,233 --> 01:00:41,270
-It'll start in Korea and go to Italy.
-And then go to Italy?

1643
01:00:41,337 --> 01:00:43,606
What's he going to make
for the Italian touch?

1644
01:00:43,673 --> 01:00:46,776
-What's he going to make?
-How will he make the transition?

1645
01:00:46,843 --> 01:00:48,711
Dang it. The string.

1646
01:00:48,778 --> 01:00:49,912
He just said, "Dang it."

1647
01:00:49,979 --> 01:00:51,914
-What's he doing? Cut it out!
-What's that?

1648
01:00:52,148 --> 01:00:53,182
IS THAT…?

1649
01:00:53,683 --> 01:00:56,386
DRAW IN MORE FOLLOWERS!

1650
01:00:56,452 --> 01:00:57,854
-What's he doing?
-What?

1651
01:00:57,920 --> 01:00:59,088
Cut it out!

1652
01:00:59,155 --> 01:01:01,691
-Jong-won did that in <i>Culinary Class Wars.</i>
-Stop it. What are you doing?

1653
01:01:01,758 --> 01:01:02,992
Are you copying Jong-won?

1654
01:01:03,059 --> 01:01:04,460
What's that? Is that a kite?

1655
01:01:04,827 --> 01:01:07,497
HE'S DOING EVERYTHING HE CAN
TO GET MORE FOLLOWERS!

1656
01:01:07,930 --> 01:01:09,132
SUDDENLY PLAYS CAT'S CRADLE…

1657
01:01:09,198 --> 01:01:10,733
-He's copying Jong-won!
-Oh, no.

1658
01:01:10,800 --> 01:01:12,268
He failed.

1659
01:01:12,335 --> 01:01:14,671
-You should've rolled it.
-It's so hard.

1660
01:01:14,737 --> 01:01:15,772
That's not for everyone.

1661
01:01:15,838 --> 01:01:17,306
It's because your arms are short.

1662
01:01:17,573 --> 01:01:18,641
LAUGHING OUT LOUD

1663
01:01:18,708 --> 01:01:20,176
You're right. His arms are short.

1664
01:01:20,243 --> 01:01:21,744
-He ties the string.
-He doesn't have to.

1665
01:01:21,811 --> 01:01:23,579
-He's tying it.
-He doesn't have to.

1666
01:01:23,646 --> 01:01:26,015
-I can't do this.
-He can't do it, so he just puts them in.

1667
01:01:26,082 --> 01:01:28,418
Don't even try it. It's upsetting.

1668
01:01:28,985 --> 01:01:31,054
But Sung-jun's Italian touch isn't ready.

1669
01:01:31,120 --> 01:01:33,089
When will it be ready?

1670
01:01:33,156 --> 01:01:34,257
It's right here.

1671
01:01:34,323 --> 01:01:35,458
That's Italy?

1672
01:01:35,525 --> 01:01:38,695
He just mixed rice with basil pesto.

1673
01:01:38,761 --> 01:01:39,762
After mixing it with butter.

1674
01:01:39,829 --> 01:01:42,565
I see. Rice was his Italian touch.

1675
01:01:42,632 --> 01:01:45,101
-Is that like arancini?
-I think so.

1676
01:01:45,168 --> 01:01:46,936
He's adding a touch of Italy
with arancini.

1677
01:01:47,003 --> 01:01:49,205
You have under six minutes left.

1678
01:01:49,272 --> 01:01:50,606
Please hurry.

1679
01:01:50,673 --> 01:01:51,574
Why is he using a bag?

1680
01:01:51,641 --> 01:01:53,009
-He'll pipe it.
-To pipe it.

1681
01:01:53,409 --> 01:01:54,410
AN EMERGENCY FOR SUNG-JUN

1682
01:01:54,477 --> 01:01:55,812
-He'll pipe it nicely.
-To pipe it.

1683
01:01:55,878 --> 01:01:57,747
WELCOMING FOLLOWERS
WITH HIS PROPELLER

1684
01:01:58,047 --> 01:01:59,248
SO TOUGH!

1685
01:02:00,583 --> 01:02:02,585
CHICKEN RILLETTES, READY TO GO

1686
01:02:03,252 --> 01:02:05,755
What was that? Was that peach jam?

1687
01:02:05,822 --> 01:02:07,590
He spins it around.

1688
01:02:07,657 --> 01:02:09,592
RAKING IN 1,000 FOLLOWERS
PER SPIN!

1689
01:02:09,659 --> 01:02:11,527
That was cool too. The spinning.

1690
01:02:11,594 --> 01:02:13,896
-Everything he does is picturesque.
-Yes.

1691
01:02:13,963 --> 01:02:16,666
-Really? That's cool?
-Do not do it. Just cook.

1692
01:02:17,567 --> 01:02:19,302
Five minutes, Jung-hwan!

1693
01:02:19,368 --> 01:02:21,137
-Yes.
-Please report from the kitchen.

1694
01:02:21,204 --> 01:02:24,340
Arancini is usually deep-fried
with breadcrumbs,

1695
01:02:24,407 --> 01:02:26,242
but without it,
he has to use frying batter.

1696
01:02:26,309 --> 01:02:27,276
The rice?

1697
01:02:27,343 --> 01:02:29,212
-He's deep-frying basil rice.
-That looks good.

1698
01:02:29,278 --> 01:02:30,813
He's deep-frying the flavored rice.

1699
01:02:30,880 --> 01:02:33,716
-Will you try the broth first?
-Less than five minutes.

1700
01:02:33,783 --> 01:02:35,585
-The pork soup.
-Yes.

1701
01:02:35,651 --> 01:02:37,787
So? Is it <i>dwaeji-gukbap?</i>

1702
01:02:37,854 --> 01:02:38,688
How's the soup?

1703
01:02:38,755 --> 01:02:40,523
Is it a fine dining experience?

1704
01:02:40,590 --> 01:02:42,525
Or is it a deadly experience?

1705
01:02:43,092 --> 01:02:44,393
It's just a garlic field.

1706
01:02:45,528 --> 01:02:47,363
It tastes too strong of garlic.

1707
01:02:47,430 --> 01:02:48,364
It has to boil for longer.

1708
01:02:48,431 --> 01:02:51,868
-The garlic…
-Well, you only have four minutes.

1709
01:02:51,934 --> 01:02:53,603
So far, it's a deadly experience.

1710
01:02:53,903 --> 01:02:56,806
JONG-WON GRABS AN APPLE

1711
01:02:56,973 --> 01:02:58,040
PEELING

1712
01:02:59,575 --> 01:03:01,210
WHAT'S THIS MACHINE?

1713
01:03:01,277 --> 01:03:02,979
Is that an apple peeler?

1714
01:03:03,045 --> 01:03:04,313
Yes.

1715
01:03:04,380 --> 01:03:06,749
Hey, wait. What?

1716
01:03:06,816 --> 01:03:08,518
REVOLVING FOOD SLICER

1717
01:03:08,885 --> 01:03:11,020
4. PEEL AN APPLE AND MAKE
NOODLES WITH A FOOD SLICER

1718
01:03:12,121 --> 01:03:13,322
The apple.

1719
01:03:13,389 --> 01:03:17,393
-He made an apple into noodles.
-He ground the apple like this.

1720
01:03:17,460 --> 01:03:18,628
Why did you do this?

1721
01:03:18,694 --> 01:03:20,730
To make them like noodles. Apple noodles.

1722
01:03:20,797 --> 01:03:23,499
I'm turning it into noodles,
preserving them, and topping the dish.

1723
01:03:23,566 --> 01:03:26,969
-You've made it into noodles.
-Do you have enough time?

1724
01:03:27,603 --> 01:03:29,205
What's that? Okay.

1725
01:03:29,272 --> 01:03:31,174
-Try it and tell us.
-What did you eat?

1726
01:03:31,974 --> 01:03:33,176
What is it? What's that?

1727
01:03:33,242 --> 01:03:34,443
I have no idea.

1728
01:03:34,510 --> 01:03:36,579
It's that paste he made
with mayonnaise and chicken.

1729
01:03:36,646 --> 01:03:38,281
Rillettes. It's a meat jam.

1730
01:03:38,347 --> 01:03:40,550
This is good.
It'll taste amazing on some bread.

1731
01:03:40,783 --> 01:03:42,785
5. SOAK APPLE NOODLES WITH
BLACK PEPPER AND CHESTNUT HONEY

1732
01:03:42,852 --> 01:03:44,587
He must've fed you
because he knew it was good.

1733
01:03:44,654 --> 01:03:46,722
I wanted him to leave my side
as soon as possible.

1734
01:03:48,624 --> 01:03:49,692
"Taste this and leave."

1735
01:03:49,759 --> 01:03:50,893
"Taste this and leave"?

1736
01:03:50,960 --> 01:03:53,162
JUNG-HWAN WILL REMEMBER THIS

1737
01:03:53,229 --> 01:03:54,864
"Stop bothering me."

1738
01:03:54,931 --> 01:03:56,532
"Stop bothering me, taste this, and go."

1739
01:03:56,599 --> 01:03:57,867
"Don't bother me."

1740
01:03:57,934 --> 01:03:58,935
I'll stick around, then.

1741
01:03:59,602 --> 01:04:00,603
STICKING CLOSER

1742
01:04:00,870 --> 01:04:01,804
WHITE BALSAMIC VINEGAR

1743
01:04:01,871 --> 01:04:03,206
Is that an apple?

1744
01:04:03,840 --> 01:04:04,807
What's that?

1745
01:04:04,874 --> 01:04:06,409
-He's like that annoying neighbor.
-He's good.

1746
01:04:06,475 --> 01:04:08,344
Sung-jun has a lot going on now.

1747
01:04:08,411 --> 01:04:09,645
The problem is time.

1748
01:04:09,712 --> 01:04:12,014
-Yes.
-They have 2 minutes and 30 seconds.

1749
01:04:12,081 --> 01:04:14,083
-Is the arancini done?
-Yes.

1750
01:04:14,150 --> 01:04:15,017
One second.

1751
01:04:15,084 --> 01:04:17,787
-Is the soup ready already?
-Wait.

1752
01:04:17,854 --> 01:04:19,555
The soup for <i>gukbap?</i>

1753
01:04:19,622 --> 01:04:21,257
-Are you just using the soup?
-Yes.

1754
01:04:21,324 --> 01:04:22,792
-What?
-Just the soup?

1755
01:04:22,859 --> 01:04:26,662
-It's a fine dining experience.
-He's pouring it into a cup.

1756
01:04:26,729 --> 01:04:28,631
Huh? Isn't that a moka pot?

1757
01:04:28,698 --> 01:04:30,166
-A coffee siphoning machine.
-It's for coffee.

1758
01:04:30,233 --> 01:04:31,801
Don't you make shots with that?

1759
01:04:31,868 --> 01:04:33,469
-Yes.
-What's that?

1760
01:04:33,536 --> 01:04:37,240
-The ground kelp and dried shiitake.
-Kelp and shiitake.

1761
01:04:37,306 --> 01:04:38,774
He's topping it on the soup.

1762
01:04:38,975 --> 01:04:40,443
WOW

1763
01:04:40,509 --> 01:04:42,845
-Wait!
<i>-Dwaeji-gukbap</i> has become fancy!

1764
01:04:42,912 --> 01:04:44,513
A minute and forty seconds left.

1765
01:04:44,580 --> 01:04:46,515
Chef Sung-jun looks very busy right now.

1766
01:04:46,582 --> 01:04:47,783
He heats it up!

1767
01:04:47,850 --> 01:04:49,619
MOKA POT IS ON THE GRILL

1768
01:04:49,685 --> 01:04:50,519
This seems odd.

1769
01:04:50,586 --> 01:04:52,121
Won't it melt? Is it okay?

1770
01:04:52,188 --> 01:04:53,923
-This is how you use it.
-That's how it's done.

1771
01:04:53,990 --> 01:04:54,824
When you boil that,

1772
01:04:54,891 --> 01:05:00,296
the soup at the bottom will rise up
and come back down with the powder.

1773
01:05:00,363 --> 01:05:02,531
-Is that how it's done?
-It's used to make coffee.

1774
01:05:02,598 --> 01:05:04,901
I've never seen anyone
make <i>dwaeji-gukbap</i> like this.

1775
01:05:04,967 --> 01:05:08,304
-Will that work?
-A minute and ten or so seconds left.

1776
01:05:08,371 --> 01:05:10,773
-You'll need to hurry!
-Plate the dishes.

1777
01:05:10,840 --> 01:05:12,441
CHIVE OIL!

1778
01:05:12,975 --> 01:05:15,177
JONG-WON'S LAST SAUCE RUSH!
+ GOLDEN ORANGE ZEST

1779
01:05:15,945 --> 01:05:18,114
MAKE SAUCE
WITH GOLDEN ORANGE ZEST,

1780
01:05:18,180 --> 01:05:20,750
OLIVE OIL, BALSAMIC VINEGAR,
AND PEPPER

1781
01:05:21,017 --> 01:05:21,851
PEPPER!

1782
01:05:23,819 --> 01:05:26,789
A minute and ten or so seconds left.

1783
01:05:26,856 --> 01:05:29,692
-Please hurry!
-Start plating it.

1784
01:05:29,759 --> 01:05:31,294
They need to start plating the dishes.

1785
01:05:31,360 --> 01:05:33,195
Yes, you have a minute and ten seconds.
It must be hot!

1786
01:05:33,262 --> 01:05:35,965
-It's all about the presentation.
-You need that shell.

1787
01:05:36,032 --> 01:05:37,767
-Don't let it break!
-It won't come off!

1788
01:05:37,833 --> 01:05:39,869
-Don't let it break, Jong-won!
-No!

1789
01:05:39,936 --> 01:05:41,470
HE GOT IT!

1790
01:05:41,537 --> 01:05:43,005
-It came off.
-It must be so hot.

1791
01:05:43,072 --> 01:05:44,707
You have under a minute.

1792
01:05:44,774 --> 01:05:46,075
Fifty seconds!

1793
01:05:46,142 --> 01:05:48,844
You must hurry up. Fifty seconds.

1794
01:05:48,911 --> 01:05:50,046
7. PUT RILLETTES
INTO TART SHELLS

1795
01:05:51,414 --> 01:05:52,248
SUNG-JUN CALCULATES THE TIMING

1796
01:05:52,315 --> 01:05:54,016
What are you calculating, Sung-jun?

1797
01:05:54,083 --> 01:05:56,152
-Is it for the fire?
-Shouldn't you take them out?

1798
01:05:56,218 --> 01:05:58,587
The kimchi? These don't seem fully cooked.

1799
01:05:58,654 --> 01:06:00,923
-Forty seconds!
-That's just raw kimchi.

1800
01:06:01,824 --> 01:06:03,259
-That's…
-Cut it.

1801
01:06:03,326 --> 01:06:05,494
-There's meat inside.
-He put meat inside.

1802
01:06:05,561 --> 01:06:07,063
It's cooked. So hot!

1803
01:06:07,129 --> 01:06:10,433
Are you sure the meat is cooked?
Thirty seconds!

1804
01:06:10,666 --> 01:06:12,835
PEACH JAM ON THE RILLETTES

1805
01:06:13,135 --> 01:06:15,004
TOPPED WITH APPLE NOODLES!

1806
01:06:15,071 --> 01:06:16,672
Jong-won's hands begin to tremble.

1807
01:06:16,739 --> 01:06:18,708
-He did that in 15 minutes?
-Undo the strings!

1808
01:06:18,774 --> 01:06:20,376
-The strings!
-Twenty seconds!

1809
01:06:20,443 --> 01:06:21,877
-The strings!
-Twenty seconds!

1810
01:06:21,944 --> 01:06:25,748
I just saw it,
and I don't think the meat is cooked.

1811
01:06:25,815 --> 01:06:27,350
-Twenty seconds!
-Hurry up!

1812
01:06:27,416 --> 01:06:28,784
Twenty seconds!

1813
01:06:29,118 --> 01:06:31,620
THE SCALLION PIECES
OPENED UP INTO V-SHAPES

1814
01:06:31,821 --> 01:06:33,255
WHAT'S THE CHERRY ON TOP?

1815
01:06:33,923 --> 01:06:35,458
ADDING DOTS OF PEACH JAM!

1816
01:06:35,524 --> 01:06:37,526
-That's so crazy.
-Seven. Six.

1817
01:06:37,593 --> 01:06:39,729
THIS IS
THE FINE DINING EXPERIENCE!

1818
01:06:40,663 --> 01:06:42,631
SUNG-JUN FINISHES
WITH AN ARANCINI ON TOP

1819
01:06:43,399 --> 01:06:45,801
JONG-WON FINISHES
WITH THE RILLETTE TART

1820
01:06:45,868 --> 01:06:48,137
-Two. One!
-Two. One!

1821
01:06:48,204 --> 01:06:49,138
Time's up!

1822
01:06:49,205 --> 01:06:51,273
-Ring the bell.
-Time's up. Ring the bell.

1823
01:06:51,340 --> 01:06:52,541
Jong-won is done too.

1824
01:06:53,309 --> 01:06:54,477
Gosh.

1825
01:06:54,543 --> 01:06:59,115
Sung-jun finished first,
so he'll go, and then Jong-won.

1826
01:06:59,181 --> 01:07:02,051
-They're both done.
-How did he do this in 15 minutes?

1827
01:07:02,118 --> 01:07:02,952
That's amazing.

1828
01:07:03,019 --> 01:07:04,053
WIDE-EYED

1829
01:07:04,120 --> 01:07:07,890
Both fine dining experiences
were put together for Jun-myun.

1830
01:07:08,224 --> 01:07:10,192
AMAZED

1831
01:07:10,259 --> 01:07:12,061
-Wasn't that an amazing battle?
-It was.

1832
01:07:12,128 --> 01:07:13,462
That looks so pretty.

1833
01:07:13,529 --> 01:07:14,663
I can't imagine the flavor.

1834
01:07:14,730 --> 01:07:16,165
-Why don't you try it now?
-Okay.

1835
01:07:16,232 --> 01:07:18,801
Chef Sung-jun finished first by a hair.

1836
01:07:18,868 --> 01:07:20,236
Please try Son Stealer.

1837
01:07:20,302 --> 01:07:22,171
KIMCHI DUMPLING AND ARANCINI
ON CHIVE OIL

1838
01:07:22,571 --> 01:07:25,007
DWAEJI-GUKBAP REINTERPRETED
WITH A TOUCH OF ITALY

1839
01:07:25,274 --> 01:07:28,778
CHEF KWON SUNG-JUN'S SON STEALER

1840
01:07:28,844 --> 01:07:31,414
Allow me to present
something I have prepared.

1841
01:07:31,480 --> 01:07:32,348
SLAP

1842
01:07:32,415 --> 01:07:34,850
You prepared something? Wait a moment.

1843
01:07:34,917 --> 01:07:38,788
You need something like this
for your first fine dining experience.

1844
01:07:38,854 --> 01:07:40,089
It can be something new.

1845
01:07:40,156 --> 01:07:41,791
COMING UP,
A NEW KIND OF PRESENTATION

1846
01:07:42,358 --> 01:07:45,961
-Those are the ingredients.
-I wanted to share the broth ingredients.

1847
01:07:46,028 --> 01:07:47,463
You're just showing her?

1848
01:07:47,530 --> 01:07:49,398
-M restaurant does that.
-"I used these."

1849
01:07:49,832 --> 01:07:53,002
BENCHMARKING
A MICHELIN 3-STAR RESTAURANT

1850
01:07:53,069 --> 01:07:54,937
-Kwon-gling Pot.
-Let me grab these

1851
01:07:55,004 --> 01:07:56,672
and set it up for you.

1852
01:07:56,739 --> 01:07:58,941
This is a part of his performance.

1853
01:07:59,008 --> 01:08:01,277
FOG BILLOWS OUT

1854
01:08:01,343 --> 01:08:04,780
As you can see,
I used 12 ingredients to make the broth.

1855
01:08:05,214 --> 01:08:06,649
THE SPEECH IS TOO SHORT

1856
01:08:06,715 --> 01:08:08,751
Did you prepare this?

1857
01:08:08,818 --> 01:08:10,019
Where did you get the dry ice?

1858
01:08:10,086 --> 01:08:12,555
While eating ice cream today, I thought

1859
01:08:12,621 --> 01:08:13,823
this might be kind of cool.

1860
01:08:13,889 --> 01:08:14,857
It looks good.

1861
01:08:14,924 --> 01:08:17,326
THE TUBBY TWINS ORDERED
ICE CREAM DURING THE BREAK

1862
01:08:17,393 --> 01:08:19,595
These are the dry ice that they give you.

1863
01:08:19,662 --> 01:08:22,031
-We had ice cream together.
-A new experience.

1864
01:08:22,098 --> 01:08:23,265
It is exotic.

1865
01:08:23,599 --> 01:08:24,667
INCREDIBLE

1866
01:08:24,733 --> 01:08:26,569
He's dying to win a star.

1867
01:08:26,635 --> 01:08:27,837
You're trying so hard.

1868
01:08:27,903 --> 01:08:28,971
Someone give him a star.

1869
01:08:29,038 --> 01:08:30,272
Now, the main dish.

1870
01:08:30,339 --> 01:08:35,678
I added ten different ingredients
to this moka pot.

1871
01:08:35,744 --> 01:08:37,179
Korea meets Italy.

1872
01:08:37,246 --> 01:08:38,380
12 INGREDIENTS ARE IN THIS BROTH!

1873
01:08:38,948 --> 01:08:40,549
HOWEVER…

1874
01:08:40,616 --> 01:08:42,284
This is why it's Italy.

1875
01:08:42,351 --> 01:08:45,454
I'm sorry,
but the fog keeps coming toward me.

1876
01:08:45,521 --> 01:08:46,355
I'm cold now.

1877
01:08:46,922 --> 01:08:50,159
AFTER ALL, THE PRESENTATION
WAS BACKED BY AN ICE CREAM PLACE

1878
01:08:50,226 --> 01:08:51,861
-All right.
-How should I eat this?

1879
01:08:51,927 --> 01:08:55,431
As I mentioned before,
it should start with Korean flavors first.

1880
01:08:55,498 --> 01:08:57,566
-May I try the soup?
-Try the soup

1881
01:08:57,633 --> 01:09:01,270
with chive oil and kimchi dumpling on top.

1882
01:09:01,337 --> 01:09:03,839
-You made dumplings?
-He did.

1883
01:09:03,906 --> 01:09:05,708
-I'll try the soup.
-The soup.

1884
01:09:06,275 --> 01:09:08,110
The Korean fine dining experience.

1885
01:09:09,211 --> 01:09:11,080
WAIT, I KNOW THIS FLAVOR!

1886
01:09:11,881 --> 01:09:14,083
I CAN TASTE ALL 12 INGREDIENTS!

1887
01:09:14,149 --> 01:09:16,085
The Korean fine dining experience.

1888
01:09:16,152 --> 01:09:17,419
Was it worth all the ingredients?

1889
01:09:17,486 --> 01:09:18,320
Yes.

1890
01:09:18,387 --> 01:09:19,455
Precisely.

1891
01:09:19,522 --> 01:09:21,157
It must be rich.

1892
01:09:21,824 --> 01:09:22,925
This is nice.

1893
01:09:22,992 --> 01:09:23,859
What's it like?

1894
01:09:23,926 --> 01:09:26,262
It's literally the pork soup
of <i>dwaeji-gukbap.</i>

1895
01:09:26,829 --> 01:09:29,498
-Does it taste like it?
-Yes, it does.

1896
01:09:29,565 --> 01:09:31,033
It tastes like meat soup.

1897
01:09:31,233 --> 01:09:32,902
NOT SO BAD

1898
01:09:32,968 --> 01:09:35,538
Just as you top <i>dwaeji-gukbap</i> with chives,

1899
01:09:35,604 --> 01:09:37,540
<i>I wanted to make chive oil</i>
<i>for the experience.</i>

1900
01:09:37,606 --> 01:09:39,675
That's why it has a refreshing aroma.

1901
01:09:39,742 --> 01:09:41,043
Does the soup taste rich?

1902
01:09:41,110 --> 01:09:43,546
Yes, it's not so light.

1903
01:09:43,612 --> 01:09:46,649
It's nothing we should devalue.

1904
01:09:46,715 --> 01:09:47,550
Does it taste Korean?

1905
01:09:47,616 --> 01:09:49,285
He did it in 15 minutes.

1906
01:09:49,351 --> 01:09:51,420
The soup is far too good to say

1907
01:09:51,487 --> 01:09:54,590
-he made it in just 15 minutes.
-In just 15 minutes.

1908
01:09:54,657 --> 01:09:56,358
-What should she eat first?
-The dumpling.

1909
01:09:56,425 --> 01:09:58,227
-The kimchi dumpling.
-This one?

1910
01:09:58,294 --> 01:10:00,763
It may not have been cooked.

1911
01:10:01,363 --> 01:10:02,865
Isn't that kimchi still raw?

1912
01:10:02,932 --> 01:10:06,402
-It's just the color. It gets cooked fast.
-It doesn't look so bad.

1913
01:10:06,468 --> 01:10:07,770
I'll try it.

1914
01:10:07,836 --> 01:10:09,071
It should be cooked.

1915
01:10:09,138 --> 01:10:11,907
Kimchi dumpling.
I wonder what that's like.

1916
01:10:11,974 --> 01:10:12,808
MMM

1917
01:10:13,475 --> 01:10:14,376
MHMM

1918
01:10:15,377 --> 01:10:16,812
I added salted hairtail for more flavor.

1919
01:10:17,146 --> 01:10:19,248
I KNEW IT! I CAN TASTE THAT!

1920
01:10:19,315 --> 01:10:21,183
Your eyes are about to pop out.

1921
01:10:21,250 --> 01:10:23,619
-Her eyes are about to pop out?
-It's good.

1922
01:10:23,686 --> 01:10:25,454
-Thank you.
-It's very refreshing too.

1923
01:10:25,521 --> 01:10:26,689
Is it?

1924
01:10:26,755 --> 01:10:28,691
It feels like
I'm eating cabbage dumplings.

1925
01:10:28,757 --> 01:10:30,759
-Cabbage dumplings?
-Yes.

1926
01:10:30,826 --> 01:10:33,996
-That's all for the Korean flavor.
-Okay.

1927
01:10:34,063 --> 01:10:35,364
Next, some rice.

1928
01:10:35,431 --> 01:10:37,433
-Is this rice?
-The arancini?

1929
01:10:37,499 --> 01:10:40,002
It's called arancini,
an Italian deep-fried rice ball.

1930
01:10:40,069 --> 01:10:41,503
-I see.
-If you break it

1931
01:10:41,570 --> 01:10:45,007
<i>and let the basil pesto and butter</i>
<i>melt into the soup, it'll taste different.</i>

1932
01:10:45,074 --> 01:10:45,908
<i>That was my intention.</i>

1933
01:10:45,975 --> 01:10:47,243
Two flavors.

1934
01:10:47,309 --> 01:10:50,512
-You have a pretty good story today.
-He does.

1935
01:10:50,579 --> 01:10:55,150
This reminds me
of a rice ball covered with fried tofu.

1936
01:10:55,217 --> 01:10:57,319
Mix it with the soup
as if it's <i>gukbap,</i> rice soup.

1937
01:10:57,386 --> 01:11:01,223
-It'll taste different once you do that.
-Korea meets Italy.

1938
01:11:01,290 --> 01:11:02,224
Let me try this.

1939
01:11:04,126 --> 01:11:04,960
HMM…

1940
01:11:06,629 --> 01:11:07,930
HAS SHE UNDERSTOOD?

1941
01:11:07,997 --> 01:11:09,932
It's taking her time to comprehend.

1942
01:11:10,399 --> 01:11:11,367
UNSURE

1943
01:11:11,433 --> 01:11:14,737
It won't be easy to understand
the mix of Korea and Italy in an instant.

1944
01:11:14,803 --> 01:11:16,338
It takes time to mingle.

1945
01:11:16,405 --> 01:11:18,307
DO THE FLAVORS
OF ITALY AND KOREA MINGLE WELL?

1946
01:11:18,374 --> 01:11:21,910
It may seem unlikely,
but it mixes well with everything else.

1947
01:11:21,977 --> 01:11:23,812
-It could feel awkward.
-It could.

1948
01:11:24,847 --> 01:11:27,116
She tries it one more time.

1949
01:11:27,182 --> 01:11:28,984
Korea meets Italy once again.

1950
01:11:29,551 --> 01:11:30,419
I hope you become friends.

1951
01:11:30,486 --> 01:11:33,222
It's very delicious with the soup,

1952
01:11:33,289 --> 01:11:35,090
-and the balance is great.
-A nice balance.

1953
01:11:35,157 --> 01:11:36,425
The flavor isn't out of place.

1954
01:11:36,492 --> 01:11:38,527
-I'm just unfamiliar with it.
-It's unfamiliar.

1955
01:11:38,594 --> 01:11:41,430
Sung-jun took quite a risk here.

1956
01:11:41,497 --> 01:11:42,731
It's stunning and delicious.

1957
01:11:42,798 --> 01:11:43,799
-I see.
-Thank you.

1958
01:11:43,866 --> 01:11:47,436
Next, Chef Jong-won's dish.

1959
01:11:47,503 --> 01:11:50,673
Les Misérables French-Style Dining.

1960
01:11:50,739 --> 01:11:51,974
CHICKEN RILLETTES
TOPPED WITH APPLE NOODLES,

1961
01:11:52,041 --> 01:11:53,042
THE ESSENCE OF FINE DINING

1962
01:11:53,442 --> 01:11:57,146
CHEF SON JONG-WON'S
LES MISÉRABLES FRENCH-STYLE DINING

1963
01:11:57,212 --> 01:11:59,481
Chef Jong-won,
do you need to provide any service?

1964
01:11:59,548 --> 01:12:02,284
-Let me just bring her this.
-He's coming.

1965
01:12:02,351 --> 01:12:04,219
Let's put those away.

1966
01:12:04,286 --> 01:12:06,355
-The dry ice.
-Let me do that.

1967
01:12:06,422 --> 01:12:08,524
That towel will
overshadow the dry ice presentation.

1968
01:12:08,590 --> 01:12:10,859
-The water keeps leaking out.
-Water leaked out.

1969
01:12:10,926 --> 01:12:13,095
What is this? Look at this water.

1970
01:12:13,162 --> 01:12:15,531
-My goodness.
-Wait, no. Emergency.

1971
01:12:15,597 --> 01:12:17,866
How is this a fine dining experience?

1972
01:12:18,233 --> 01:12:20,336
POONG REPRIMANDS HARSHLY

1973
01:12:20,402 --> 01:12:23,739
Most fine dining restaurants
create fog while hiding the dry ice,

1974
01:12:23,806 --> 01:12:26,675
<i>but he kept in the open.</i>

1975
01:12:27,309 --> 01:12:29,478
-It's like a dish I made.
-It looks messy.

1976
01:12:29,545 --> 01:12:32,247
-He said it was like his dish.
-Chef Jong-won brought a wet towel.

1977
01:12:32,314 --> 01:12:36,118
It has a nice texture for your fingertips,
so please try it with your hand.

1978
01:12:36,185 --> 01:12:38,754
-Oh, my.
-So it's for you to wipe your hands.

1979
01:12:38,821 --> 01:12:40,456
He added another detail.

1980
01:12:40,522 --> 01:12:41,557
-Yes?
-Why don't you smell it?

1981
01:12:41,623 --> 01:12:42,658
-This thing?
-Yes.

1982
01:12:42,725 --> 01:12:44,693
HE SERVED THE TOWEL
WITH A NICE SCENT

1983
01:12:44,760 --> 01:12:45,961
Actually, I have a stuffy nose.

1984
01:12:46,228 --> 01:12:49,098
HIS DETAIL COULD NOT REACH
BEYOND HER STUFFY NOSE

1985
01:12:49,164 --> 01:12:53,335
-He dropped some lemon juice on it.
-Why don't you smell it, Poong?

1986
01:12:53,402 --> 01:12:54,803
It must smell like it.

1987
01:12:54,870 --> 01:12:56,972
It smells like lemon,

1988
01:12:57,039 --> 01:12:59,475
and it helps you relax.

1989
01:12:59,541 --> 01:13:04,179
Chef Jong-won was sitting here
during the entire shoot today, wasn't he?

1990
01:13:04,246 --> 01:13:06,014
I thought he had eyes on this side

1991
01:13:06,081 --> 01:13:08,350
because he grabbed tissue for me

1992
01:13:08,417 --> 01:13:10,719
-and kept an eye on me the whole time.
-He's considerate.

1993
01:13:10,786 --> 01:13:13,856
So he already gets 26 points for this.

1994
01:13:14,990 --> 01:13:15,824
Nice try.

1995
01:13:15,891 --> 01:13:16,759
NICE TRY, SUNG-JUN

1996
01:13:16,825 --> 01:13:19,294
But the dry ice he served

1997
01:13:19,361 --> 01:13:22,664
was something you could see,
so it could've been moving.

1998
01:13:22,731 --> 01:13:24,900
She couldn't smell the towel
because of her stuffy nose,

1999
01:13:24,967 --> 01:13:27,102
but he still got 26 extra points.

2000
01:13:28,570 --> 01:13:30,439
We're on an uneven playing field.

2001
01:13:30,506 --> 01:13:31,974
What if I had prepared the towel?

2002
01:13:32,040 --> 01:13:35,210
But our viewers await
your objective review.

2003
01:13:35,277 --> 01:13:36,412
-Use your hand.
-Use your hand.

2004
01:13:36,712 --> 01:13:39,448
FIRST, FEEL THE TEXTURE

2005
01:13:39,515 --> 01:13:41,016
-That's just one bite.
-What now?

2006
01:13:41,083 --> 01:13:43,352
-Should I eat everything?
-As much as you can bite.

2007
01:13:43,419 --> 01:13:44,820
-All right.
-Split it into three bites.

2008
01:13:44,887 --> 01:13:47,189
-There's sauce underneath.
-Let me try it.

2009
01:13:48,223 --> 01:13:50,559
YUM

2010
01:13:52,494 --> 01:13:54,263
It's in French style.

2011
01:13:54,830 --> 01:13:56,198
THE FRESHNESS SWIRLS
IN HER MOUTH

2012
01:13:56,265 --> 01:13:58,267
<i>It'll be a true fine dining experience.</i>

2013
01:13:58,333 --> 01:14:00,335
It's in French style.

2014
01:14:01,069 --> 01:14:01,970
Wow.

2015
01:14:03,038 --> 01:14:04,440
What's it like?

2016
01:14:04,506 --> 01:14:07,876
It tastes quite sour,

2017
01:14:07,943 --> 01:14:10,145
and it's the kind
that cheers you up instantly.

2018
01:14:10,212 --> 01:14:12,481
The apple he used here

2019
01:14:12,548 --> 01:14:13,949
is so delicious.

2020
01:14:14,016 --> 01:14:16,385
He turned the apple into noodles
because she likes them.

2021
01:14:16,452 --> 01:14:18,120
-He did that.
-He did it for a reason.

2022
01:14:18,420 --> 01:14:21,256
THE LAST BITE

2023
01:14:22,224 --> 01:14:24,660
THE FROWN OF TRUTH

2024
01:14:24,726 --> 01:14:28,430
That was made
with the smoked chicken your husband got.

2025
01:14:28,497 --> 01:14:30,199
-Can you taste it?
-Can you?

2026
01:14:30,265 --> 01:14:33,101
If you hadn't mentioned it,
I wouldn't have noticed.

2027
01:14:33,168 --> 01:14:37,639
I usually don't enjoy smoked food,
but it doesn't taste like it.

2028
01:14:38,674 --> 01:14:39,875
-He hid it well.
-Yes.

2029
01:14:39,942 --> 01:14:41,443
<i>He hid it with mayonnaise.</i>

2030
01:14:41,510 --> 01:14:44,046
<i>I peeled off the skin</i>
<i>and used just the meat.</i>

2031
01:14:45,180 --> 01:14:47,182
-I'm simply amazed.
-All right.

2032
01:14:47,249 --> 01:14:49,351
-Time to decide.
-You must decide now.

2033
01:14:49,418 --> 01:14:51,787
-So…
-May I add one more thing?

2034
01:14:51,854 --> 01:14:54,990
I didn't think the towel
would count as a part of the dish,

2035
01:14:55,057 --> 01:14:57,693
so I prepared that after the time was up.

2036
01:14:57,759 --> 01:15:00,395
You said it added extra points,

2037
01:15:00,462 --> 01:15:01,697
so I'm concerned about that.

2038
01:15:01,763 --> 01:15:03,432
Do not give him the extra points for that.

2039
01:15:03,765 --> 01:15:04,600
FAIR-HEARTED

2040
01:15:04,666 --> 01:15:06,335
-I didn't want a misunderstanding.
-Back to zero.

2041
01:15:06,401 --> 01:15:08,003
-All right.
-You get 26 points deducted.

2042
01:15:08,070 --> 01:15:10,339
-I'll do it fairly.
-Yes, fairly.

2043
01:15:10,405 --> 01:15:12,808
Chef Sung-jun, do you want to include
your little performance

2044
01:15:12,875 --> 01:15:14,209
in the evaluation or not?

2045
01:15:14,276 --> 01:15:15,744
-Of course, I do.
-Yes?

2046
01:15:15,811 --> 01:15:18,680
-He already lost.
-He should've said no.

2047
01:15:18,747 --> 01:15:20,215
I won't include it.

2048
01:15:21,083 --> 01:15:22,885
JEEZ

2049
01:15:22,951 --> 01:15:25,587
-Just the dish.
-Please focus on just the food.

2050
01:15:25,654 --> 01:15:29,391
Which dish did Jun-myun like better?

2051
01:15:29,458 --> 01:15:30,826
<i>Press one for Jong-won</i>

2052
01:15:32,160 --> 01:15:34,062
<i>and two for Sung-jun.</i>

2053
01:15:34,796 --> 01:15:38,333
It's another moment of joy and heartbreak.

2054
01:15:38,400 --> 01:15:39,301
Make your decision

2055
01:15:39,368 --> 01:15:41,470
and press the button!

2056
01:15:43,005 --> 01:15:44,072
MADE HER CHOICE

2057
01:15:44,139 --> 01:15:45,474
Jun-myun made her decision.

2058
01:15:45,541 --> 01:15:48,577
Which one of them will be the winner?

2059
01:15:48,644 --> 01:15:50,812
Who gave you
a better fine dining experience?

2060
01:15:50,879 --> 01:15:52,347
Show us the result!

2061
01:15:52,414 --> 01:15:54,917
If Jong-won wins,

2062
01:15:54,983 --> 01:15:57,619
he'll rise to joint first place
along with Eun-yeong.

2063
01:15:57,686 --> 01:15:59,187
If Sung-jun wins,

2064
01:15:59,254 --> 01:16:01,790
he'll earn his first star of this season.

2065
01:16:01,857 --> 01:16:03,592
Jong-won versus Sung-jun!

2066
01:16:03,659 --> 01:16:05,027
Who did Jun-myun choose?

2067
01:16:05,093 --> 01:16:07,029
Whose fine dining experience was better?

2068
01:16:08,196 --> 01:16:09,831
Who's the winner?

2069
01:16:09,898 --> 01:16:11,600
SON JONG-WON WINS

2070
01:16:12,034 --> 01:16:13,135
LES MISÉRABLES FRENCH-STYLE DINING WINS

2071
01:16:13,201 --> 01:16:14,336
It's Jong-won!

2072
01:16:14,770 --> 01:16:16,672
THE FINAL BOSS OF
THE FINE DINING INDUSTRY DELIVERS

2073
01:16:16,738 --> 01:16:18,640
It's Jong-won.

2074
01:16:18,707 --> 01:16:21,443
Sung-jun fails
to surpass Jong-won once again.

2075
01:16:21,510 --> 01:16:23,111
And he now has fewer followers.

2076
01:16:23,178 --> 01:16:26,982
-And losing in the number of followers.
-The towel won against the dry ice.

2077
01:16:27,049 --> 01:16:29,818
It wasn't because the food tasted bad.

2078
01:16:29,885 --> 01:16:32,821
Among the dishes I had today,
this was seasoned best for my taste.

2079
01:16:32,888 --> 01:16:35,757
-I see.
-It was seasoned perfectly,

2080
01:16:35,824 --> 01:16:39,428
but it was far from the vibe
of the fine dining experience I expected.

2081
01:16:39,494 --> 01:16:43,432
This felt like a dish of soup
at a North Korean-style dumpling place.

2082
01:16:43,498 --> 01:16:46,001
It tastes like a delicious bowl
of Pyongyang-style dumpling soup.

2083
01:16:46,068 --> 01:16:48,904
It missed what I was looking for.

2084
01:16:49,871 --> 01:16:51,773
-A miss.
-What a shame, Sung-jun.

2085
01:16:51,840 --> 01:16:55,611
Jong-won, you now have two stars.

2086
01:16:55,677 --> 01:16:58,947
I had an advantage as someone who has been
in the fine dining industry longer.

2087
01:16:59,014 --> 01:17:00,449
I thought about

2088
01:17:00,515 --> 01:17:03,552
what I was doing
when I was Sung-jun's age,

2089
01:17:03,619 --> 01:17:06,722
and I was nowhere near his position then.
He's already doing so well.

2090
01:17:06,788 --> 01:17:10,058
I'm sure he'll do very well
by the time he's my age,

2091
01:17:10,125 --> 01:17:13,762
so I'll continue to stay sharp.

2092
01:17:15,664 --> 01:17:17,933
I'm so glad he's not my peer.

2093
01:17:18,400 --> 01:17:19,701
THE HEART THAT JUST WANTS TO WIN

2094
01:17:20,202 --> 01:17:21,436
IT HAPPENS AT HIS AGE

2095
01:17:21,503 --> 01:17:23,005
That's how you're going to respond?

2096
01:17:23,071 --> 01:17:25,707
-What a relief.
-Sung-jun has a bright future ahead.

2097
01:17:25,774 --> 01:17:27,075
-This is just the beginning.
-Yes.

2098
01:17:27,142 --> 01:17:31,213
Jun-myun, please put a star on Jong-won!

2099
01:17:31,279 --> 01:17:32,948
This is his second star!

2100
01:17:33,815 --> 01:17:36,418
Eun-yeong and Jong-won
are now in joint first place.

2101
01:17:36,485 --> 01:17:38,286
-Thanks, Sung-jun.
-Congratulations!

2102
01:17:38,353 --> 01:17:39,588
-No stars.
-Congratulations!

2103
01:17:39,655 --> 01:17:41,156
Jong-won takes his second star.

2104
01:17:41,223 --> 01:17:42,724
STAY TUNED FOR THE PREVIEW

2105
01:17:43,291 --> 01:17:46,061
<i>Please welcome</i>
<i>the hottest chefs of </i>Chef & My Fridge.

2106
01:17:46,128 --> 01:17:48,063
<i>It's time for the chefs to party!</i>

2107
01:17:48,130 --> 01:17:49,331
TODAY IS THE CHEFS' DAY TO PARTY

2108
01:17:49,398 --> 01:17:52,501
<i>The winner</i>
<i>of 2026 </i>Chef & My Fridge<i> Awards is…</i>

2109
01:17:52,868 --> 01:17:54,236
WHO IS THE WINNER OF THE AWARD

2110
01:17:54,302 --> 01:17:55,203
THAT WILL SHOCK EVERYONE?

2111
01:17:55,270 --> 01:17:56,838
How much more must I try to get it?

2112
01:17:56,905 --> 01:17:58,473
Please welcome today's fridge owners!

2113
01:17:58,540 --> 01:17:59,808
-Come on!
-What?

2114
01:17:59,875 --> 01:18:02,377
Chef Son Jong-won
and Webtoon Artist Kim Poong!

2115
01:18:02,444 --> 01:18:05,480
What does the chef who has
double Michelin stars keep in his fridge?

2116
01:18:05,547 --> 01:18:08,583
-These are tightly aligned.
-I got tired as soon as I opened it.

2117
01:18:08,650 --> 01:18:09,718
I rarely get food delivered.

2118
01:18:09,785 --> 01:18:10,752
I rarely eat <i>ramyeon.</i>

2119
01:18:10,819 --> 01:18:12,788
I crave something
with a crunch at night, so…

2120
01:18:12,854 --> 01:18:13,789
That's nonsense.

2121
01:18:13,855 --> 01:18:15,657
I drink carbonated water
when I want something spicy.

2122
01:18:15,724 --> 01:18:16,858
He's way too strict.

2123
01:18:16,925 --> 01:18:18,493
I don't know why, but I want to copy him.

2124
01:18:18,760 --> 01:18:19,928
THE MOST SELF-CONTROLLED FRIDGE

2125
01:18:19,995 --> 01:18:22,030
Who will Chef Jong-won choose?

2126
01:18:22,097 --> 01:18:23,098
What's going on?

2127
01:18:23,331 --> 01:18:25,467
A DISH EXPLODING WITH DOPAMINE

2128
01:18:25,534 --> 01:18:26,702
It looks so good.

2129
01:18:26,768 --> 01:18:27,803
Three knives!

2130
01:18:27,869 --> 01:18:29,337
-Three knives?
-He fried those.

2131
01:18:29,404 --> 01:18:30,772
Did you enjoy your meal?

2132
01:18:31,006 --> 01:18:32,040
COMES WITH THE FINEST SERVICE

2133
01:18:32,107 --> 01:18:33,575
I can do this for Jong-won!

2134
01:18:33,942 --> 01:18:35,711
EVEN THE FRIDGE OWNER COOKS
HERE ON CHEF & MY FRIDGE

2135
01:18:35,777 --> 01:18:38,080
I must let loose and start digging in.

2136
01:18:38,146 --> 01:18:39,481
It's been suffocating him.

2137
01:18:39,548 --> 01:18:40,582
It's making me let loose.

2138
01:18:40,649 --> 01:18:42,284
He hasn't binged for a long time.

2139
01:18:43,852 --> 01:18:45,887
-Sorry, Nam-no.
-Let's share!

2140
01:18:45,954 --> 01:18:47,322
I'll be Son Nam-no today.

2141
01:18:47,389 --> 01:18:48,523
No!

2142
01:18:58,533 --> 01:19:03,338
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn

